<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Party Official Quits Parliament in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Former Mpumalanga premier
Mathews Phosa announced Thursday that he is leaving parliament and
the government service for the private sector.
</P>
<P>
But he dispelled earlier speculation that he was to quit
politics.
</P>
<P>
"It is my intention to remain an active African National
Congress (ANC) member and continue serving my country, but from a
different platform," he told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Phosa said his decision followed consultation with the ANC
leadership as well as colleagues who had been deployed in the
private sector or those who were there for their own account.
</P>
<P>
"From all these consultations I have received nothing but good
advice, support and encouragement," he said.
</P>
<P>
He rejected suggestions that he was bitter at having been
replaced as Mpumalanga premier to become an ordinary backbencher
in parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said his experience from years in politics showed him that
the country still had a long way to go before reaching the ideal
of a better life for all.
</P>
<P>
"Our struggle has not only been a political one, but has had an
economic focus as well. Without economic support for our political
objectives we have no hope of achieving our goals," he said.
</P>
<P>
Phosa was one of three ANC premiers who had been axed before
the June 2 general election. His province was plagued by
allegations of corruption and party in-fighting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
