<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Economy to Bottom Out: Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"It is expected that economic growth will be just below one
percent in 1999. However, it is believed that most of this growth
will only materialize in the second half of this year," the group
noted in its latest quarterly economic review.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's economy grew by 0.1 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
ABSA predicted that the economy would grow by two percent in
the second half of 1999 compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Positive spin-offs from the demutualization of the country's
leading insurer, Old Mutual, a slight increase in the commodity
price and lower interest rates will support the recovery in the
economy, it said.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth of two to 2.5 percent is forecast for the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
ABSA was less optimistic about the continuation of the surplus
on the current account of the balance of payments that was
registered in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
"Despite an expected increase in international commodity prices
in the remainder of 1999, a recovery in the domestic demand, a
lower international gold price, agricultural imports and a high
oil price, may push the current account back into deficit in the
second half of 1999."
</P>
<P>
The banking group remains bullish on the short-term
inflationary outlook.
</P>
<P>
"Low inflation in trading-partner countries and the relative
stability in the rand exchange rate will most probably support a
stable to lower inflation rate in the next six months."
</P>
<P>
It forecast the consumer inflation could fall below five
percent in the second half of this year. Meanwhile, the downward
trend of interest rates might well continue into 2000, it said.
</P>
<P>
ABSA expects a prime lending rate of 15.5 percent by year-end,
with a bottoming-out at around 14 percent during 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
