<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Molecule Helps Improve Bone Marrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli researchers have
developed a new molecule that can keep the body's original cells
multiplying without maturation, an achievement that may improve
bone marrow transplantation and advance gene therapy research.
</P>
<P>
Professor Michel Revel and his team at the prestigious
Weizmann Institute of Science created the new molecule which can
allow blood stem cells, the most primitive and immature cells in
the body, to survive and proliferate in test tubes, according to a
report released by the institute Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In bone marrow transplantation, stem cells are infused into a
patient to replace defective or malignant marrow. But presently it
is difficult to make stem cells of the donor multiply without
changing their properties because they quickly mature into
various types of blood cells when isolated in test tubes.
</P>
<P>
In their study, Weizmann Institute scientists developed a new
molecule by fusing together a molecule stimulating stem cells to
form clusters with it and its receptor molecule.
</P>
<P>
When the new molecule, called "chimera," was added to isolated
stem cells together with other cytokines, the cells were able to
survive in the test tube for two weeks and their numbers increased
significantly.
</P>
<P>
By transplanting the treated human stem cells to mice with
severe combined immunodeficency, the scientists verified their
ability to repopulate the bone marrow and produce all types of
blood cells, demonstrating that the stem cells had indeed remained
immature.
</P>
<P>
If the Weizmann Institute molecule is adopted for clinical
use, allowing stem cells to survive longer and increasing their
numbers, the success of bone marrow transplantation can be
improved, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The study may also provide a boost to gene therapy research by
giving scientists a larger window of opportunity for inserting
genes into human stem cells maintained in the laboratory, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Since transplanted stem cells repopulate the bone marrow of
the recipient and produce billions of blood cells every day,
inserting a gene in these cells prior to transplantation would
ensure a steady supply of the protein made by this gene,
compensating for the genetic defect causing diseases, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
