<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Employment Cost Rises 1.1 Percent in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 29 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department reported
Thursday that Employment Cost Index, considered the best measure
of changes in wages and benefit costs, increased 1.1 percent in
the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
It is the biggest quarterly increase since 1991, but followed a
record low 0.4 percent rise during the first three months of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The lowest unemployment rate in 29 years has raised fears that
employers scrambling for workers will have to raise wages, and
therefore prices.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report, meanwhile, the Labor Department said that
the number of people filing new claims for unemployment benefits
dropped last week to the lowest level in two years, indicating the
labor market continues to tighten.
</P>
<P>
Jobless claims fell 40,000 to 275,000 in the week ending on
July 24, lowering a four-week moving average of claims to 300,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
