<HEADLINE> Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALEXANDRIA (Egypt) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on
Thursday committed himself to the Wye peace agreement with the
Palestinians, but said he wants to make changes if Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat agrees.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak after their meeting in Alexandria, 220 kilometers
northwest of Cairo, Barak said he would like to modify the Wye
River accord, but "only if we agree upon it with Chairman Arafat
(of the Palestinian National Authority)."
(BC-Egypt-Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Eight Iraqi civilians were killed and 26 others
injured on Thursday in U.S. and British warplanes bombardment of
some civilian and service facilities in southern and northern
Iraq, said an Iraqi military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 6:10 (0210 GMT), eight formations of
enemy warplanes coming from Saudi bases violated southern Iraqi
airspace over Muthana, Najaf, Kerbala and Wasit provinces.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes attacked some civilian and service facilities
in Wasit province, 180 kilometers to the southeast of Baghdad,
killing eight civilians and injuring 25 others, said the
spokesman. (BC-Iraq-US Attacks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is due to be in Egypt
on Saturday for talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in
Alexandria on the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, a Palestinian
diplomat said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zohdi al Qedra told reporters
that Arafat and Mubarak are expected to "lay down a mechanism for
action for the coming period to put the Middle East peace process
on the right track." (BC-Egypt-Palestinians-Arafat) 
</P>
</TEXT>
