<HEADLINE> Russia Wants to Be Equal Member in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin said here Thursday that his country must become "an
equal member of the European Union" and called for the lifting of
restrictions in trade and economics.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin made the statement at a press conference following
his meeting with Finnish Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen and EU
Foreign Affairs Commissioner Hans Van den Broek.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "Russia must participate on equal conditions in
all economic projects on liquidating the aftermath of the Yugoslav
crisis," the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin said he and Lipponen had managed to discuss many
aspects of trilateral trade and economic ties, which are to be
sorted out shortly "in a constructive way."
</P>
<P>
Lipponen, for his part, said that the three-party talks ahead
of the Russia-EU summit scheduled for October had also touched
upon nuclear security, environmental protection and cooperation in
power engineering.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek said such problems as certification,
standardization and overflight of Siberia must be solved before
the Russia-EU summit in Helsinki, Finland.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are scheduled to hold a meeting of experts Friday
on the fourth and fifth tranches of EU food aid to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the EU are also working on an agreement on
scientific cooperation in satellite navigation and a project
code-named "Galileo," Tass said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
