<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan says Poverty Growth Is Scandalous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 29 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Thursday drew the world's attention to the growing poverty
and urged the international community to do more to address the
trend.
</P>
<P>
The number of people living in absolute poverty has
substantially increased in the past decade with 3 billion poor
people in the world today, he told a human development forum at
the U.N. headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
"It will be time enough to start congratulating ourselves when
we have reversed this scandalous trend," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, there are "public bads" or "problems without
passports" to be addressed, such as global warming, infectious
diseases, drugs and international crime, terrorism and weapons
proliferation, he added.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that these should be the focus of the next year's
Millennium Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Some 250 policy-makers, academics and development specialists
are gathering here for a three-day debate on key issues and
innovations in human development concepts and strategies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
