<HEADLINE> Arafat, Mubarak to Hold Talks Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat is
due to be in Egypt on Saturday for talks with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak in Alexandria on the Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks, a Palestinian diplomat said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zohdi al Qedra told reporters
that Arafat and Mubarak are expected to "lay down a mechanism for
action for the coming period to put the Middle East peace process
on the right track."
</P>
<P>
"Playing with time and ideas and procrastinations has raised
doubts over (Israeli Prime Minister Ehud) Barak's intentions
toward peace," al Qedra said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority "firmly rejects Barak's
proposal to delay withdrawal of Israeli troops from the West Bank
and combine the Wye River accord with the final status talks," he
said.
</P>
<P>
After the elections in May, Barak has repeatedly expressed
readiness to carry out the Wye accord signed last October by
Arafat and former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who
then froze the deal after the first of the three-phase troops
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Barak has proposed to combine the third phase of pullback with
the more complicated final status talks after implementing the
second phase.
</P>
<P>
But Arafat has said he would not accept any modifications to
the agreement and insisted on quick Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Al Qedra urged the United States, a key mediator in the Mideast
peace process, to "stand by the side of the Palestinian legitimate
rights" and pressure the Israeli government to enforce the signed
agreements, foremost the Wye River agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. is the sponsor of and witness to the peace process
and should not lose its credibility in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian diplomat praised Egypt's leading role in
supporting the Palestinian cause and activating the peace
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
