<HEADLINE> 2 Officers Killed in PKK Mine Attack in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Two military personnel were killed
on Thursday in a mine explosion in eastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The mine, planted by rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK), exploded when a military vehicle on duty hit it in
Semdinli town of Hakkari province bordering Iran, leaving one
officer and one soldier dead, and another soldier wounded in the
explosion, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli has
accused Iran of hosting and supporting PKK rebels, a charge
categorically denied by Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Late Wednesday night, a group of PKK rebels opened fire at a
Turkish military vehicle on duty on the construction site of
Alparslan-1 Dam near Bulunik town of Mus province in southeast
Turkey, killing one soldier, wounding one officer and six soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a war since 1984 for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Their fighting is still
going on though their captive PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan was
sentenced to death last month by Turkey's Ankara State Security
Court.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts between the Turkish security forces and the PKK
militants have claimed over 37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
