<HEADLINE> Taliban Control Strategic District with Great Casualties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban
managed to hold the strategically important district of Nejrab in
control as their summer offensive against the northern alliance
forces entered the second day Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Figures of casualties from various sources indicated that at
least 120 Taliban soldiers had been killed in the battle around
the district of Nejrab, northeast of the capital city of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
However, most of the district and the main city of Nejrab
remained in Taliban hands after it was seized Wednesday, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Nejrab is one of seven known entry points into the Panjsher
Valley, stronghold of the forces loyal to former defense minister
Ahmad Shah Masood.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the anti-Taliban forces continued their rocket
attack on Kabul. Five rockets struck the capital Thursday, but no
report on casualties is available so far.
</P>
<P>
An opposition spokesman said fighting was heavy on the Old Road
and the New Road overnight and fresh fighting erupted early
Thursday afternoon at Koh-e-Safi.
</P>
<P>
The Old and New Roads are about 25 kilometres north of Kabul,
the near-by mountain range of Koh-e-Safi is to the east, and
further east are the twin districts of Nejrab and Tagab.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, which control more than 80 percent of Afghanistan,
early Wednesday began a major offensive aimed at wiping out
opposition forces.
</P>
<P>
The militia have claimed a steady advance towards the Panjsher
Valley through Nejrab. 
</P>
</TEXT>
