<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Announces Strike for Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 29 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi opposition will
stage a 30-hour hartal (destructive strike) early next month to
protest the government's decision on Wednesday to study the
transshipment of Indian goods through Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance, comprising the major opposition - the
Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP), the Jatiya Party, the
Jamaat-e-Islami and the Islami Oikya Jote, made the announcement
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The hartal will start at 6 a.m. on August 2 and ends at 12 noon
on August 3.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the opposition announced a countrywide demonstration
on August 3, to protest against the "price hike rise in
electricity rate and deterioration of law and order."
</P>
<P>
The opposition organized a three-day road march from Sunday to
Tuesday, the second of its kind this year, to different corners of
the country to intensify the anti-government agitation.
</P>
<P>
Oli Ahmed, member of the BNP Standing Committee, denounced the
government decision on transit to India, saying that "The cabinet
decision about conceding transit facility to India would
ultimately jeopardize security of Bangladesh," a press report
said.
</P>
<P>
He refuted the suggestion that the transit would bring economic
benefit for Bangladesh. "It's a bluff to divert the people's
attention," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
