<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Sustain International Pressure on UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 29 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) Thursday
reiterated that it will sustain its strong international pressure
on Angola's rebel National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) through strictly abiding by relevant U.N. Security
Council resolutions on sanctions.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed in a statement by EU president which was
handed to Angolan Foreign Minister Joao Miranda Thursday by
Portuguese and French ambassadors and EU representative in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The EU will strictly abide by U.N. resolutions which include
arms, diamond export sanctions and oil embargo on UNITA, the
closing up of UNITA' s offices abroad and prohibition of foreign
visit by UNITA officials.
</P>
<P>
The statement signed by the 15 EU members also urged Jonas
Savimbi, chairman of the rebel movement, to stop all war
operations which have been incurring humanitarian tragedy to the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
In the mean time, the EU expressed its appreciations of the
Angolan government for its reform measures aimed at stabilizing
national economy and financial situation.
</P>
<P>
Since the country's civil war was renewed at the end of last
year, the Angolan government has repeatedly accused some European
and African countries of providing secretly weaponry and logistic
goods to UNITA.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the U.N. Security Council has set up an ad hoc
committee to investigate violations of relevant resolutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USAID Experts to Visit Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 29 (Xinhua) -- A group of experts from the U.S.
International Development Agency (USAID) will start their visit to
Angola on Friday to inspect and study the situation of
humanitarian aid in the country.
</P>
<P>
Heather Evans, an official with USAID, told local press
Thursday that the 5-member group will consider the possibility of
offering humanitarian aid to those victims of war living in places
with access difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Evans refused to reveal the details of their mission in Angola,
but said that the group would contact the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
In Angola, there are 1.7 million displaced people, two million
victims living in rebel-besieged areas and 750,000 abandoned or
handicapped children and orphans. According to the Angolan
authorities, the country needs a minimum humanitarian aid of 200
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the United Nations Economic and Social Council
(UNESC) held in Swiss this month, the United Nations solicited the
international community for a humanitarian aid of 105 million U.S.
dollars, but obtained only 40 million dollars in donations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
