<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The World Bank has agreed to extend loans of 1.6
billion U.S. dollars this year to six Arab states, namely, Egypt,
Jordan, Morocco, Tunisia, Yemen and the Palestinian National
Authority, to help finance 25 development projects in these
countries.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Arab daily "Al Hayat" quoted a recent World Bank
statement as saying that 550 million dollars will be allocated to
Egypt, 210 million dollars to Jordan, 440 million to Morocco, 194
million to Tunisia, 54 million to the Palestinian self-rule areas,
and 181 million to Yemen.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi government will pay back some 770 million
rials (25 million dollars) of debts to local farmers and
contractors this week, the Al Hayat reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bankers in Saudi Arabia anticipate a rise of some 30 billion
rials (8 billion dollars) in government revenues this year as a
result of improved oil prices and the government measures to
stimulate non-petroleum income resources.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Health Ismail Sallam anticipates
a rise in Egypt's export of medical drugs to exceed 340 million
dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Egyptian daily "Alam Al Yom" quoted him as saying
that Egypt's export of medical drugs have already exceeded 300
million dollars since the begining of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian-made drugs meet about 95 percent of domestic needs, he
said, adding that market prices have not changed since 1997.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABIE -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) is the third
largest re-export center in the world, after Hong Kong and
Singapore, the Alam Al Yom reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a recent study by the economic research
department of the UAE Industrial Bank as saying that the volume of
re-export trade in UAE has reached 24 billion dirhams (6.5 billion
dollars), or one third of the country's trading sector.
</P>
<P>
The study said Iran is the foremost destination of UAE
re-exports, accounting for 20 percent of the total, followed by
India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
