<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-29 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8 Iraqi Civilians killed in Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Eight Iraqi civilians were killed
and 26 others injured on Thursday in U.S. and British warplanes
bombardment of some civilian and service facilities in southern
and northern Iraq, said an Iraqi military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 6:10 (0210 GMT), eight formations of
enemy warplanes coming from Saudi bases violated southern Iraqi
airspace over Muthana, Najaf, Kerbala and Wasit provinces.
</P>
<P>
These warplanes attacked some civilian and service facilities
in Wasit province, 180 kilometers to the southeast of Baghdad,
killing eight civilians and injuring 25 others, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
This is the second heaviest civilian casualties caused by
U.S. and British air raids in two weeks this year in their
regular attacks on Iraqi civilian and military targets.
</P>
<P>
On July 18, U.S. and British bombardment of civilian
buildings in southern Iraq led to the deaths of 17 civilians
and the injuries of dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 10:30 (0630 GMT), nine formations
of U.S. and British warplanes coming from Turkish airspace also
violated northern Iraqi airspace over Dohuk, Neineva and Erbil
provinces in the day.
</P>
<P>
These enemy planes bombed some civilian and service
installations in the region, leading to the injury of one
civilian, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back at the invading
enemy planes and forced them to flee, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency said that residents in Kut, capital
city of Wasit province, held funeral procession for the victims
of the bombardment later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in
Iraq in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim
of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims
in the south from any possible attacks by the government
troops.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's U.S.-British airstrikes, Iraq has
declared that it does not recognize the restricted zones because
they were imposed unilaterally by the U.S. and Britain without
the authorization of the U.N. Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balkan Leaders Gather For Post-Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Finnishi President and current
European Union president Martti Ahtisaari said here Thursday that
the Stability Pact for Southeastern Europe should become a turning
point.
</P>
<P>
He opened a two-day summit of Stability Pact when leaders of
states and governments from Balkan region gathered in Sarajevo,
the capital of Bosnia and Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
"It is my hope that this meeting will be developed to
constructive brainstorming about how to begin implementation of
the tasks of the three working tables in the Stability Pact:
Democracy and human rights, economic reconstruction, development
and cooperation, and security issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari also noted that tensions and crises have erupted
throughout the the Balkan region, caused refugee flows and
instability, devastated economies. "These crises have cost
southeastern Europe precious time and set it back in its
aspiration to join the rest of Europe," he added.
</P>
<P>
He believe it is high time to make up for lost time, saying the
successful management of transition throughout the region is a
prerequisite for functional integration into broader European and
international structures. "The challenges of integration are
extraordinary, but so are the potential rewards."
</P>
<P>
The Balkan leaders are trying to set out their priorities for
the region before the full-scale summit starts on Friday, which
will be attended by some 40 world leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Thursday's summit was attended by the leaders from Albania,
Bulgaria, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Hungary, Romania,
Slovenia, Switzerland, Turkey, Former Yugoslavia republic of
Macedonia and some international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The countries neighboring Yugoslavia suffered a lot during
NATO's 78-day air bombing against Yugoslavia. They want the West
to give them compensation for the their loss from the war.
</P>
<P>
Donors of rich countries and international financial agencies
promised on Wednesday in Brussels 2.1 billion U.S. dollars for
urgent humanitarian aid in Kosovo before Winter sets in and to
launch the reconstruction process in the whole region except for
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
But the summit meeting here is more symbolic than substantial
as analysts predict. "To ensure sustainable peace we must build on
a comprehensive vision of longer-term democratic governance,
economic growth and security cooperation," Ahtisaari said.
</P>
<P>
The Stability Pact is an initiative which seeks to bring
together not only the countries most affected by regional
instability, but also all their partners at the highest political
level, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
