<HEADLINE> Kenyan Children Discuss Environmental Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 29 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 children from all
parts of Kenya gathered here Thursday to open the first Kenya
National Children's Conference on Environment with a focus on
links between communications and environment.
</P>
<P>
The young delegates aged nine to 13 are expected to present
their papers on environmental issues and answer questions from
fellow representatives.
</P>
<P>
"Each year, millions of children die of environmental causes.
Children' s health is an index of the quality of the environment,"
said Shafqat Kakakhel, deputy executive director of the United
Nations Environment Program (UNEP).
</P>
<P>
The first of the major two objectives for the conference is to
promote environmental awareness among children and the second is
to share their views and aspirations on environmental protection,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The discussions of the participants cover such topics as "Poor
communications and environmental pollution", "Creating
environmental awareness for the conservation of wildlife" and
"Media and the Environment".
</P>
<P>
The conference is set to be a forum at which children will
articulate their vision for the next millenium.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is also a follow-up to the International Children's
 Conference on the Environment, held in Nairobi in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
