<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Economy Slows Abruptly in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. economic growth slowed
abruptly to 2.3 percent during the second quarter, according to
advance estimates released Thursday by the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
The Department reported that the gross domestic product, the
nation's total output of goods and services, increased by 44
billion dollars from April through June to an inflation-adjusted
7.8 trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The deceleration in GDP in the second quarter primarily
reflected a deceleration in personal consumption expenditures and
a downturn in government spending that more than offset an upturn
in exports, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The second-quarter slowdown came after the economy surprised
many analysts by growing at a bigger-than-expected 4.3 percent
annual rate during the first three months of 1999. Economists have
been predicting that slower growth would calm fears that the
economy could overheat. They noted new restraint by consumers,
whose purchases account for two-thirds of the nation's economic
activity, was largely responsible for putting on the brakes.
</P>
<P>
The report said consumer spending grew by 4 percent from April
through June, compared with a torrid 6.7 percent during the first
three months of 1999. It was the slowest spending increase since
the fourth quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
An inflation gauge tied to the GDP showed consumer prices rose
more quickly during the Spring, at an annual rate of 2.1 percent,
compared to 1.2 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Worrying that economic growth is too rapid and might spark
inflation, the Federal Reserve in June raised interest rates by a
quarter of a point. In his midyear report to Congress this week,
Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan repeated warning the nation's central
bankers have not ruled out another rate increase this year if
inflation flares.
</P>
<P>
During the lingering international financial crisis, overseas
markets for American products have dwindled and a flood of imports
from troubled countries trying to unload their own goods here at
discount prices has helped keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
However, there has been some recent improvement in the trade
picture as foreign economies have begun to recover. The record
U.S. trade deficit shaved just 0.75 percent off total economic
growth in the second quarter of 1999, compared to a 2.23 percent
offset in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Investment by U.S. businesses, spending on new equipment and
plants, picked up from April through June, growing by 10.8
percent, compared to 8.5 percent in the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter, rising mortgage rates dampened the
housing market, with spending on new homes and apartments growing
by 5.1 percent, much slower than the 15.4 percent rate in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Although consumers tempered their buying spree in the second
quarter, they are still spending more than they earn. The personal
savings rate, savings as a percentage of disposable income, fell
to a record low -- negative 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the Department emphasized that the second-quarter
"advance" estimates are based on source data that are incomplete
or subject to further revision by the source agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
