<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Mourns Over Slain Tamil Parliamentarian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 29 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan cabinet of
ministers Thursday expressed their grave sorrow and sadness over
the killing of Tamil parliamentarian Neelan Thiruchelvam by a
suicide bomber.
</P>
<P>
The ministers observed two-minute silence in his honor at their
cabinet meeting, the Government Information Department said in a
press release.
</P>
<P>
Thiruchelvam, 55, a member of the moderate Tamil United
Liberation Front (TULF), was killed instantly Thursday morning at
a stone's throw from his home in Colombo's upmarket diplomatic
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The bomber jumped off the back of a motorcyclist and onto
Thiruchelvam's car as it approached a busy intersection, police
said.
</P>
<P>
The bomber also was killed in the explosion, police said. Five
others were injured in the blast, including two of the
parliamentarian's bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
No one claimed responsibility, but officials blamed the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), which is fighting a
16-year war for an independent Tamil homeland.
</P>
<P>
Thiruchelvam's TULF party said his killing highlighted the need
for a settlement of the burning ethnic issue in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"The tragic death...once again emphasizes the urgent need to
evolve a peaceful political resolution to the country's national
conflict," a TULF statement said.
</P>
<P>
The deaths of three other TULF politicians have also been
blamed on the LTTE rebels, including the assassination of the
party's founder Appapillai Amritalingam in the 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
