<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balkan Leaders Gather for Post-Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Finnish President and current
European Union president Martti Ahtisaari said here Thursday that
the Stability Pact for Southeastern Europe should become a turning
point.
</P>
<P>
He opened a two-day summit of Stability Pact when leaders of
states and governments from Balkan region gathered in Sarajevo,
the capital of Bosnia and Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
"It is my hope that this meeting will be constructive about how
to begin implementation of the tasks of the three working tables
in the Stability Pact: Democracy and human rights, economic
reconstruction, development and cooperation, and security issues,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari also noted that tensions and crises have erupted
throughout the the Balkan region, caused refugee flows and
instability. "These crises have cost southeastern Europe precious
time and set it back in its aspiration to join the rest of
Europe," he added.
</P>
<P>
He believes it is high time to make up for lost time, saying the
successful management of transition throughout the region is a
prerequisite for functional integration into broader European and
international structures. "The challenges of integration are
extraordinary, but so are the potential rewards."
</P>
<P>
The Balkan leaders are trying to set out their priorities for
the region before the full-scale summit starts on Friday, which
will be attended by some 40 world leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Thursday's summit was attended by the leaders from Albania,
Bulguria, Bosnia and herzegovina, Croatia, Hungary, Romania,
Slovenia, Switzerland, Turkey, Former Yugoslavia republic of
Macedonia and some international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The countries neighboring Yugoslavia suffered a lot during
NATO's 78-day air bombing against Yugoslavia. They want the West
to give them compensation for their loss from the war.
</P>
<P>
Donors of rich countries and international financial agencies
promised on Wednesday in Brussels 2.1 billion U.S. dollars for
urgent humanitarian aid in Kosovo before winter sets in and to
launch the reconstruction process in the whole region except for
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
But the summit meeting here is more symbolic than substantial
as analysts predict. "To ensure sustainable peace we must build on
a comprehensive vision of longer-term democratic governance,
economic growth and security cooperation," Ahtisaari said.
</P>
<P>
The Stability Pact is an initiative which seeks to bring
together not only the countries most affected by regional
instability, but also all their partners at the highest political
level, he said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union president stressed that the solutions for
the region must be generated within the region. "Sarajevo, where
the tortured history of this century can be seen to have begun,
can now help launch a new century of peace, prosperity and
democracy," he said in his opening statement at the first day of
the two-day summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
