<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Lowers Maize Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 29 (Xinhua) --- Kenya cut its tariff on maize
imports to 25 percent from 32.5 percent Thursday in a bid to
increase supply shortly after the state-run National Cereals and
Produce Board said commercial stocks were running low.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry announced that it was also waiving an
additional 50 percent suspended duty on maize after an expected
poor harvest meant Kenyans would have insufficient supply of
their major food.
</P>
<P>
The suspended duty is an additional discretionary tax which the
 government usually imposes to protect its farmers when imports
are seen to harm local growers.
</P>
<P>
The National Cereals and Produce Board (NCPB) said Tuesday its
stocks had fallen to 700,000 bags (90 kms per bag) from 2.3
million at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of remaining stock is government owned for use mainly
for famine relief, NCPB said.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said the country needed to import at least two
million 90-kg bags to meet its needs in one to two months before
the next harvest.
</P>
<P>
Scarce rains during the main rainy season between March and
June have undermined crop prospects for 1999.
</P>
<P>
Kenya did not officially export any maize from the 1998 crop
but analysts reported smuggling to neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
