<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Four-year Economic Plan Approved by Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 29 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government's four-year
economic blueprint, the Dpef, crossed its last parliamentary
hurdle Thursday when it won approval by the Lower House.
</P>
<P>
The Dpef, the document giving the economic guidelines and
forecasts on which next year's budget will be based later in the
year, was approved by the Italian Senate Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The final version makes no mention of the contentious pension
reform issue, which will be taken up with the trade unions in
September.
</P>
<P>
It cites only plans to "rationalize" welfare agencies and to
boost supplementary pension schemes. Overall, it aims to get the
budget deficit down to just 0.1 percent of gross domestic product
by 2003, cutting public debt below 100 percent of GDP by the same
year.
</P>
<P>
The government motion on the blueprint also includes an
explicit request for moves with Italy's European Union partners to
review the criteria for evaluating how members of the euro zone
calculate their deficits.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of deficit to GDP is a key factor in membership of
the euro zone, whose members are governed by a Stability and
Growth Pact designed to ensure that they maintain their finances
within the euro zone's requirements.
</P>
<P>
According to the motion, given the euro zone's economic
stability and low inflation, the pact should be revised to exclude
from the reckoning public expenditure to stoke growth.
</P>
<P>
Other key proposals include a reduction in the tax burden,
lower taxes on the sale and purchase of small family firms, larger
tax breaks for families earning less than 60 million lire (about
33 thousand U.S. dollars) a year, and an extension of tax breaks
on home building work until the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to spend 3.5 trillion lire (about 2
billion U.S. dollars) on growth next year, with the revenue coming
from recouped taxes and fines for dodged taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Cut Number of Ministries to Twelve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 29 (Xinhua) -- The Italian cabinet Thursday evening
approved a reform that will eventually cut the number of
ministries from eighteen to twelve.
</P>
<P>
The reform will be made by incorporating some ministries into
others, merging some with others, and getting rid of some.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema has been a strong
proponent of the move as a way of achieving a more wildly and
efficient executive.
</P>
<P>
No changes are envisaged for the interior, foreign, justice,
agriculture and defense ministries.
</P>
<P>
Two economic ministries will be created, one merging the
Treasury and finance ministries, the other merging the
communications, industry, farm and foreign trade ministries.
</P>
<P>
Two other new ministries "for the territory" will be set up to
incorporate environment, transport, public works with navigation
and land protection with infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
The education ministry will be merged with that of universities
and scientific research, and there will be a single ministry for
cultural activities and the cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
The health ministry will be merged with the labor and social
policy ministries.
</P>
<P>
Alongside the ministries, twelve new agencies will spring up to
speed the wheels of government.
</P>
<P>
The reform will come into effect with the next legislature but
some effects such as the reforms of the finance and education
ministries and the creation of new agencies are expected to take
place sooner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
