<HEADLINE> Another British GM Crop Test Site Attacked by Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 29 (Xinhua) -- British police confirmed Thursday
that a test site of genetically-modified (GM) oilseed rape in
northern England has been damaged by environmental activists, the
second such attack in Britain in a week.
</P>
<P>
The 2.5 acre crop, near Malton, North Yorkshire, was damaged on
Wednesday, the police said. The test site was trampled by foot or
something being dragged across the crop.
</P>
<P>
A person claiming to be an activist rang two local newspapers
claiming responsibility for the destruction, and a farm manager
confirmed the damage.
</P>
<P>
Farmer Robert Hambridge, who owns the field, said that the
protesters had "spoiled a very useful trial", the results of which
are believed to be answering some of the questions in the current
debate about GM crops.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't set up for commercial purposes, it was for the
environment, to see the effect of GM crops," Hambridge was quoted
by a BBC report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The attack comes after police arrested at least 20 people in
eastern England on Monday after Greenpeace activists destroyed
half a test crop of genetically modified maize. 
</P>
</TEXT>
