<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell sharply
Thursday as a government report on wage rise triggered fears about
higher interest rates among investors.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 180.78 at
10,791.29. The blue index fell as much as 258.04 in the session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also sharply lower. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 24.37 at 1,341.03 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 65.83 at 2,640.01.
</P>
<P>
The market plunged as the Labor Department reported that its
Employment Cost Index rose 1.1 percent in the second quarter, the
bigger-than-expected rise after a 0.4 percent increase in the
first quarter. The index is considered the best measure of changes
in wages and benefit costs.
</P>
<P>
Investors feared that The Federal Reserve would use the data as
a reason for raising interest rates to curb inflation. The Federal
Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan told the House Banking Committee
last week that if new data suggest that the pace of increase in
labor cost and price will be picking up, the Federal Reserve will
have to act "promptly and forcefully" to prevent any revival of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Concerned with the data release, investors did not get any
pleasure from the other report on GDP. The Commerce Department
said in the report U.S. economic growth slowed abruptly to 2.3
percent in the second quarter, showing no overheating in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 9.59 at 630.81 and the American
Stock Exchange index fell 5.01 at 784.59. The Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies fell 5.09 at 441.58.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 11-to-4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,250 down, 799 up and 497
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 762.00 million shares from 688.93
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
