<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Seize Strategic Hill in Offensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
Friday occupied a strategic hill on the third day of its summer
offensive against the rival Northern Alliance bases north of
capital Kabul.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Afghan Islamic Press quoted a spokesman for
opposition commander Ahmad Shah Masoon as saying that the Barekab
height overlooking the Bagram airbase fell to the Taliban, who
were now just six kilometers away from the airbase.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman promised a "bloody fight" in the coming days as
the Taliban had advanced about seven kilometers on the so-called
New Road leading to the opposition-held Bagram and Qara Bagh
areas.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban Friday also launched two attacks on the Kohistan
district from Nejrab, which were repulsed by the Northern
Alliance, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban occupied Nejrab on the first day of their
offensive. Nejrab is the seventh known entry to the Panjsher
valley, the stronghold of Masood, former defense minister.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that the Taliban warplanes bombed
Charikar, capital of the Parwan province, Kohistan and other
adjoining areas.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban were reported to be advancing on Charikar from the
Pul-e-Matak side after crossing the Ghorband pass.
</P>
<P>
The AIP said that the Taliban forces suffered heavy casualties
in their attack on the Bagram airbase as the area was heavily
mined. At least 50 people from both sides were killed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the AIP said that the Taliban have launched a major
offensive against the Mahmoud Raqi, the opposition-controlled
capital of northern Lapisa province.
</P>
<P>
Other reports reaching here from Kabul said that most of the
Masood forces have retreated from the strategic Bagram airbase
north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The opposition troops have taken positions to the north and
west of the airbase while the Taliban forces were advancing from
the eastern and southern sides, said the reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
