<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Income Rises 0.7 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. personal income rose in
June and outpaced spending for the first time since January.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department said Friday that personal income, which
includes wages, interest and government benefits, rose 0.7 percent
last month, the biggest income gain since a 0.9 percent rise in
last November.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, spending picked up only 0.3 percent in June, the
smallest increase since November 1998, when spending rose 0.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
Since consumer spending has repeatedly outpaced incomes, the
nation's savings rate has set a string of record lows this year.
</P>
<P>
But in June, the savings rate was minus one percent, better
than the record low of negative 1.4 percent set in May.
</P>
<P>
June's 0.7 percent increase in income followed gains of 0.3
percent in May and 0.5 percent in April, while June's 0.3 percent
rise in spending followed increases of 0.6 percent in May and 0.5
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
Economists said a major reason for the negative saving rate is
that the strong stock market is boosting Americans' net worth and
making them feel more comfortable about dipping into savings to
pay for their spending spree.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the Labor Department reported that U.S. wages and
benefits surged in the second quarter of the year by the largest
amount since 1991. The news sent stocks tumbling on investor
worries that the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates again,
possibly as soon as its August 24 meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
