<HEADLINE> Lee Teng-Hui Should Not Be Insincere: Article </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Lee Teng-hui can countermand his "
two States" statement, but he should not act shamelessly in going
back on his own word, according to a signed article released here
today by the Xinhua News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Lee denied that he had made the "two States" statement when he
talked to a Japanese scholar attending a seminar in Taiwan on July
26, and assumed an air of being treated wrongly, the article says.
</P>
<P>
Actually, on July 9 in an interview with a German radio station,
Lee said that cross-Straits relations should be defined as "state-
to-state or at least special state-to-state relations."
</P>
<P>
Then why did Lee Teng-hui deny what he had said? People can
find the answer in the opposition voiced by the international
community and people on both sides of the Taiwan Straits after Lee
's "two States" statement was dished out, the article says.
</P>
<P>
A great number of countries have reiterated their stance of
adhering to the "One China" policy and opposing the "two States"
statement. United States President Bill Clinton talked with
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, reaffirming the U.S.'s steadfast
commitment to the "One China" policy and guaranteeing that the U.S.
policy remains unchanged. Some American politicians and portions
of the press criticized Lee as a "trouble maker" and a man who "
rocks the boat," and called his "two States" statement an "act of
provocation."
</P>
<P>
Because Lee still clings to the "two States" statement, all his
arguments speak insincerely and are, of course, unconvincing. He
failed to touch the crucial point: that his "two States" statement
is a negation of the "One China" principle, the article notes.
</P>
<P>
There is only a way out for Lee Teng-hui. That is to
countermand the "two States" statement, acknowledge his mistake,
and openly declare that he will not violate the "One China"
principle, the article concludes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
