<HEADLINE> Over 35% Russians Earn Less Than Subsistence Minimum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, July 30 (Xinhua) -- As many as 51.7 million Russians, or
35.3 percent of the country's population, earned less than the
official subsistence minimum in the first half of the year, the
State Statistics Service said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a dramatic rise from the same period of
last year, when only 22.4 percent of Russians -- 32.9 million --
were in this category. The percentage for the whole of 1998 was 23.
8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Russia's official subsistence level changes every month, but
monthly average in the first half year was 872 rubles (about 36 U.
S. dollars), the Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
