<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Erodes Purchasing Power of Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The persistently high levels of
inflation in Zimbabwe have significantly eroded the purchasing
power of the Zimbabwean dollar and has led to increases of cash in
settling domestic trade transactions, the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The upsurge in the demand for cash by the public is linked to
rising inflation, which increased year-on-year from 20.1 percent
in December, 1997 to 46.6 percent by the end of 1998 and further
to 55.2 percent in June, 1999," the central bank said in its
weekly Economic Highlights.
</P>
<P>
To accommodate the rising demand for cash, currency issued by
the bank had correspondingly risen.
</P>
<P>
The demand for currency, which was stable prior to 1997, had
risen significantly in the last one-and-half years due to
inflation.
</P>
<P>
This represented annual growth rates of 25.6 percent and 47.2
percent in December, 1998 and May, 1999 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The bank said although confidence in the use of cheques and
electronic money had increased substantially, some retailers and
merchants still insisted on cash to settle transactions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bank said, some wholesalers and retailers were
cutting down on long-term credit thereby increasing the need for
consumers to carry more cash.
</P>
<P>
The bank said most economic agents hedged against inflation by
investing in real assets.
</P>
<P>
It said high domestic inflation also encouraged economic agents
to hold foreign currency, not only as a store of value, but also
as a means of making domestic payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Moves to Reduce Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government has instituted
measures to reduce poverty and curb crime in the country, chief
government spokesman Newstead Zimba said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Among the steps the government has taken is to strengthen the
agriculture sector so that all categories of farmers' produce
surplus are for sale, said Zimba, who is also Information
Minister.
</P>
<P>
The government is encouraging the private sector and the Food
Reserve Agency to make agricultural inputs such as seeds and
fertilizers available to the farmers in good time for the farmers
to produce good yields, he said.
</P>
<P>
The farmers will be exempted from paying duty on imported
agricultural machinery in order to help them boost production.
</P>
<P>
Zimba appealed on all able-bodied Zambians, especially the
youth, to take advantage of the conducive environment to engage in
productive farming.
</P>
<P>
"I call upon the youth especially to take this challenge
seriously. They do not need to start big, but in a small way," the
minister said, adding poverty reduction will help in curbing crime
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
