<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sensex Down By 61.08 Points in Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Equities generally drifted
further downwards Friday in dull activity causing a fall of over
61 points in the benchmark index on the Bombay Stock Exchange
(BSE) due to selling in the form of squaring up positions by
operators.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index opened marginally down at 4,590.48
points and gradually moved downwards to the day's low of 4,526.80
before closing at 4,542.34 as against Thursday's close of
4,603.42, netting a loss of 61.08 points, or 1.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Institutional Investors (FIIs) and Financial
Institutions had reportedly withdrawn from the market that had
witnessed continuous flow of discouraging corporate news with
several major companies announcing quarterly working results below
the market expectations.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-100 index lost by 26.64 points to 1,988.06 from the
previous close of 2,014.70 points.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the Dollex were quoted substantially down at
454.13 and 174.65 compared with the previous close of 459.56 and
176.62 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Share prices also declined sharply on the National Stock
Exchange in Mombay due to withdrawal of support from FIIs and
domestic funds.
</P>
<P>
The market opened on a weak note and sentiment remained
depressed throughout the trading session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
