<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Deny Osama Leaving Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's ruling Taliban
Friday denied press reports that Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden
wanted the United States is planning to leave the country, said
the News Network International of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"It is an absolutely baseless report that Osama has either left
or is planning to leave Afghanistan," Maulvi Wakil Ahmed
Mutawakil, Taliban senior spokesman was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the Afghan Islamic Press reported that Osama has
decided to leave Afghanistan fearing the United States might
attack the country.
</P>
<P>
Similar mixed messages had been heard from the Taliban on Osama
earlier this month as Maulvi admitted that the alleged terrorist
was still in Afghanistan only one day after Taliban supreme leader
Mulla Mohammad Omar rejected any knowledge about Osama's
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
Accused by the United Stated of masterminding the bomb blasts
at U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania last August, Osama was
announced missing in February this year.
</P>
<P>
However, he was reported late June to have been seen in the
eastern Afghan city of Jalalabad and then the Taliban said he was
still in the country and under tight security.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been demanding the extradition of Osama
but the Taliban ruled out that possibility.
</P>
<P>
The latest rumors said Osama has expressed his desire to leave
Afghanistan and the Taliban have endorsed his decision.
</P>
<P>
On hearing the news, thousands of Afghan people Friday held
rallies and demonstrations in the eastern Afghan cities of Khost
and Jalalabad to protest against the U.S. policy on Osama, saying
that they would not hand their "guest" Osama over to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The United States stuck Khost with cruise missiles last August
following bomb blasts at its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
