<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Leaders Meet in Sarajevo on Balkan Stability Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from the 15 European
Union (EU) member states and 13 other countries gathered here
Friday to start discussions on the proposed Stability Pact for
Southeast Europe.
</P>
<P>
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, whose country holds the
current rotating European Union (EU) presidency, said that the
proposed Southeast Europe Stability Pact envisions a Europe at
long last "undivided, prosperous and free, a Europe where war
becomes unthinkable."
</P>
<P>
"Let this vision guide our talks today," he said when giving
his opening speech as chairperson of the summit.
</P>
<P>
"Southeastern Europe has been in the focus of international
attention because of the crises and tensions associated with it in
the past decade. everyone has felt the destabilizing and
demoralizing effects of practicing ideologies of hatred,
intolerance and violence," Ahtisaari said.
</P>
<P>
"It is no coincidence that today's summit meeting is being held
here in Sarajevo. This city, which has taken its place in the
history of our century, is now being called upon to help launch a
new millennium," Ahtisaari said. "You all know the symbolic value
of this venue."
</P>
<P>
Ante Jelavic, chairman of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency,
said the stability pact to be adopted by the summit will enable
all the countries in the region to join Euro-Atlantic integration,
particularly the EU and the Partnership for Peace program.
</P>
<P>
"I also think that today's inauguration of the Stability Pact
will immutably change the way of communication between the
countries in the region, as well as the global attitude towards
the region of Southeastern Europe," Jelavic said.
</P>
<P>
"This new mode of cooperation and a strong integration
dimension will permanently end the cycle of brutal conflicts that
have characterized the region so far," he added.
</P>
<P>
The stability pact for Southeast Europe was agreed by major
western powers in June. Attending the summit are leaders from the
15 EU member states, nine non-EU European countries, the United
States, Canada, Japan and Russia, as well as major international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, leaders from the EU and the Balkan countries held
a brief meeting on the Germany-proposed pact, which has already
been endorsed by most Balkan countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
