<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Protests to U.N. Over Destruction of Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has protested to the United
Nations over the destruction of the samples of VX gas found in the
Baghdad laboratory of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on
disarming Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A four-member U.N. technical team, charged with destroying or
removing toxic chemicals left behind by UNSCOM when it pulled out
of Iraq last December on the eve of a massive U.S.-British
airstrikes on Iraq, destroyed the samples on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Iraq's Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said the U.N. unreasonably rejected
Iraq's demand to keep the samples for investigation of what Iraq
accused as UNSCOM's frame-up against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM announced in 1998 there were traces of VX on parts of
Iraqi missile warheads fragments.
</P>
<P>
A United States army lab said in July, 1998 its tests on Iraqi
missile fragments proved the charge, while a similar test in a
French lab was considered inconclusive and the results of a Swiss
examination were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi media have accused UNSCOM of having contaminated the
missile fragments with the VX samples, a suspicion raised by
Russia, China and France.
</P>
<P>
Iraq charged that the U.S. and Britain opposed the analysis of
the VX samples for fear that the UNSCOM plot be uncovered.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the U.N. team was defined on the basis of a
letter sent to the Security Council by former UNSCOM chairman
Richard Butler, an Australian who was accused by Iraq of spying
for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the U.N. Security Council members refused to
amend the mandate to include analysis of the VX gas samples found
in the UNSCOM laboratory
</P>
<P>
Aziz said in his letter that the U.N.'s refusal to change the
team's original mandate," despite that new truth had been
revealed," caused harm to the credibility and impartiality of the
U.N.
</P>
<P>
He requested that a neutral professional team with diplomats
representing the Security Council be sent to check everything
existed in UNSCOM headquarters in Baghdad "in order to get
acquainted with all the facts." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
