<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down On Illegal Foreign Exchange Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration of
Foreign Exchange (SAFE) said today that a massive operation
carried out by related departments against illegal foreign
exchange trading has achieved initial results.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the SAFE said that by the end of June, more
than 260 people engaged in illegal foreign exchange trading had
been seized and more than 50 trading sites smashed, as law-
enforcement departments confiscated large sums of money used for
illegal trading.
</P>
<P>
Since China reformed its foreign exchange system in 1994, the
exchange rate of the yuan has been rectified, and foreign
exchanges are settled in banks with the currency convertible under
current accounts.
</P>
<P>
"The normal demand for foreign exchange by institutions and
individuals in China can be satisfied under the new system," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, lawless persons engaged in smuggling, tax
swindling, and money laundering have been found to use the black
market to obtain foreign exchange for their unlawful activities,
seriously disrupting the country's economic and financial order.
</P>
<P>
To stop such illegal practices, the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, China's top legislature, in December
1998 passed a decision to crack down on illegal foreign exchange
trading and to punish such crimes.
</P>
<P>
The operation was launched last April jointly by the SAFE, the
Ministry of Public Security, and the State Administration for
Industry and Commerce, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government's efforts in fighting against
illegal foreign exchange trading will not end as long as the black
market exists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
