<HEADLINE> Yeltsin: "Rebuild Friendly Relations" With West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said Friday that it is
a "strategic" task for Russia to "rebuild friendly relations" with
Western countries which were ruined after NATO's air strikes
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yeltsin said, Moscow would continue to stick to the
principle of a multipolar world. "We are fighting for this and
will not go back on it."
</P>
<P>
The "Yugoslav situation" should be "evened out" and Russia
should "rebuild the friendly relations with the United States,
Germany, France and other states that we had before," Yeltsin said
in the Kremlin before meeting with Russian Pension Fund Chairman
Mikhail Zurabov.
</P>
<P>
That is a "strategic, global task," the Interfax news agency
quoted Yeltsin as saying.
</P>
<P>
Russia froze its ties with NATO after the alliance launched
the 78-day bombing campaign against Yugoslavia and relations
plunged to their lowest ebb since the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Yeltsin, who returned to work
earlier this week after cutting short his summer vacation, had
called for relations with the West to be repaired in full.
</P>
</TEXT>
