<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Information Industry Sees Fast Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wu told a meeting that economic returns and service quality in
the industry have both been improved.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in the January-June period, the turnover
of the post and telecommunication sector totaled 148.1 billion
yuan, up 32 percent over the same period last year, while the
electronics sector grew 25.7 percent to complete an added value of
36.67 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year, the country completed
fixed assets investment of 38.8 billion yuan in postal and
telecommunications projects.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the balance of postal savings deposits had
increased by a year-on-year 19.3 percent to reach 340.5 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Wu noted that the policy of adjusting average
telecommunications charges this March, especially the slashing of
installment fees on fixed phones, helped stimulate a surge in
business volume.
</P>
<P>
On July 19, China Telecom declared that it had 100 million
fixed-telephone customers.
</P>
<P>
The turnover in the mobile phone sector jumped 87 percent on a
year-on-year basis to reach 66.59 billion yuan during the period,
accounting for 47.8 percent of the total turnovers in
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The reform on China Telecom is also underway. By the end of
June, 27 provinces and municipalities had completed the separation
of mobile telecommunications from China Telecom branches.
</P>
<P>
Wu admitted that some difficulties still exist in the industry,
citing a slower growth of fixed-assets investment, and an upturn
in losses in the electronics industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
