<HEADLINE> Mozambicans Urged to Face AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal
Mocumbi said here Friday that the Mozambicans should face the AIDS
disease and treat AIDS patients fairly.
</P>
<P>
"We want AIDs patients and AIDS virus carriers to stand forward
 bravely and educate the youth with their own lessons so as to cut
down infection rate," he told a press briefing here in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from the country's Health Ministry showed
that 700 Mozambicans are infected with AIDS virus daily. At
present, the number of children orphaned by their AIDS-infected
parents has reached 150,000. It is estimated that by the year
2005, 26 percent of Mozambican children under five years of age
will die of the killer disease. The prime minister also noted
the necessity of opening sex education courses at school. 
</P>
