<HEADLINE> ARATS Spokesman Refutes Taiwan's Distortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) has rejected a written speech by
Koo Chen-fu sent by the Taiwan's Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF)
today, saying it seriously violates the "One China" principle
already reached by both sides of the Taiwan Straits in 1992.
</P>
<P>
According to an ARATS official, ARATS President Wang Daohan
made a speech on July 12, demanding that his counterpart, Koo Chen-
fu, chairman of the SEF, clarify Li Teng-hui's and his own remarks
on redefining the relations of the two sides as "state-to-state"
relations.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan authorities made no response for 18 days, and this
afternoon faxed ARATS a letter and a written speech by Koo Chen-fu,
which preached more fallacies on the "special state-to-state
relations," the official said.
</P>
<P>
This once again lays bare the attempts of Lee Teng-hui to cling
to splittism. His acts have seriously deteriorated cross-Straits
relations and destroyed the basis of contacts and dialogue between
ARATS and SEF. Lee Teng-hui should bear full responsibility for
all the consequences arising from this, the ARATS official said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China, said in a speech delivered in 1995, "On
the premise that 'There is only one China,' we are prepared to
talk about any matter." However, Koo's speech intentionally
distorted and garbled Jiang's statement and dodged the "One China"
principle, the official said.
</P>
<P>
It is known to all that there is only one China in the world
and Taiwan is a part of China. The government of the People's
Republic of China is the sole legitimate government representing
the whole of China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Both the "two states" theory and "special state-to-state
relations" preached by Lee Teng-hui are opposed by the Chinese
people and can't be accepted by the international community, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
"We as always advocate that the "One China" policy should be
adhered to in handling cross-Straits relations, especially in
negotiations between the two sides, before realizing reunification
of the motherland. China's sovereignty and territorial integrity
brooks no separation. Only under the "One China" principle can the
two sides of the Taiwan Straits talk about reunification on the
basis of equality," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan racked its brains in vain in describing the
understanding by both sides of the Taiwan Straits on "adhering to
the 'One China' policy" as "One China with different oral
explanation," he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
