<HEADLINE> UN Officials: Situation in Kosovo Needs to be Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sarajevo, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Senior United Nations officials
agreed here Friday that situation in Kosovo needs to be improved
and they have to do their best to make things better there.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Paul Klein, special representative designated by the UN
secretary-general, told reporters that UN Balkan officials
attending the Stability Pact Summit here agreed that the Kosovo
issue is crucial and they will be doing everything to help Bernard
Kouchner, UN Interim Administrator of Kosovo, in doing the
daunting job there.
</P>
<P>
"But we cannot deflect attention from the real challenges that
remain elsewhere in the region. And I think we have all taken note
of the fact that the problems associated with the dissolution of
the former Yugoslavia cannot be created in a piecemeal fashion,
and that they require resolution in a broader European context,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have made real progress, but the road is long, the scars
are deep, and the needs are great," Klein added.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Stability Pact is "a new way of thinking, a
new approach, and a new context." It is the promise of the Balkans
' future integration into Europe, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Stability Pact for Southeast Europe, which was agreed by
major Western powers in June, is being launched today. The
Stability Pact Summit here involves the 15 European Union member
states, nine non-EU European countries, plus the United States,
Canada, Japan and Russia, as well as major international
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
