<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Families of Embassy Attack Victims Grateful For Care (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The elderly parents of Shao
Yunhuan will move to a three-room flat this October, bidding
farewell to their current one-room apartment. The local government
of Shao's hometown, Jiamusi city, Heilongjiang province, has
fulfilled Shao's wish to "give my parents a spacious house as a
gift".
</P>
<P>
"Yunhuan has just done what she should do, and the Communist
Party and government have paid such great attention to us," said
Shao Yunhuan's father, Shao Fangyuan. "Yunhuan's spirit will also
be touched," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shao Yunhuan, a journalist with the Xinhua News Agency, was
killed in a U.S. bombing of China's Embassy in Yugoslavia on May 8,
together with Xu Xinghu and Zhu Ying, both correspondents with
China's Guangming Daily.
</P>
<P>
In Danyang City in east China's Jiangsu Province, Xu's hometown,
the local party committee and government appropriated money for Xu
's parents. Xu's laid-off sister was also re-employed.
</P>
<P>
Since the incident took place, the families of the three
martyrs and wounded embassy staff have been much in the thought of
party organizations and governments at various levels, as well as
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
On May 12, Chinese President Jiang Zemin and other top leaders
went to the Xinhua News Agency and the Guangming Daily to mourn
the martyrs and express their sympathy to the families. Top
leaders have also visited the hospital to extend their wishes to
those wounded in the attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
