<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Families of Embassy Attack Victims Grateful For Care (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs, relevant local governments, and
leaders of the Xinhua News Agency and the Guangming Daily have
sent pensions and condolence money to the families of the victims.
Leaders of the two news organizations also visited them frequently
and helped resolve their difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Cao Lei, the son of Shao Yunhuan, the Xinhua reporter, was
enrolled by the Beijing International Studies University to study
the Serbian language.
</P>
<P>
The Reference News Department of Xinhua, where Shao had worked,
has promised that Cao Lei can come to the department to continue
his mother's work, if he wishes.
</P>
<P>
Shao's husband, Cao Rongfei, was severely injured in both eyes
during the embassy attack. He has received the best possible
medical treatment in Beijing, along with other injured embassy
staff members.
</P>
<P>
In addition, many people from across the country have written
to offer him their corneas. Following medical treatment, Cao's
corrected eyesight has been markedly improved.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Fulai, father of Zhu Ying, said he has received more than
200 letters from people nationwide, ranging in age from 70 to
primary school children.
</P>
<P>
In these letters, they expressed their strong sympathy and
support for Zhu's family and their utmost indignation against the
brutal actions of the U.S.-led NATO, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
"One day when I was shopping at the market, an elderly man came
to realize that I am the father of Zhu Ying. He said nothing but
just bowed to express his feelings," said Zhu during an interview
with Xinhua on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that on another occasion, a young man he did not know
wrote to him that "although you lost a child, we are now all your
children."
</P>
<P>
"Over the past months, I can feel sympathy, encouragement, and
support from people wherever I go," Zhu said. "My whole family is
very grateful for the care shown by the Party and people."
</P>
</TEXT>
