<HEADLINE> Australian Sharemarket Tumbles Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
tumbled lower Friday with banking stocks among the biggest losers
after fears of an interest rate hike were reignited in the United
States overnight.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index offloaded 40.1 points to
3,019.9, recovering from its intra-day low of 3,013.0 points.
</P>
<P>
On the local bourse, the all industrials index slid 73.8 points
to 5,253.2, while the all resources index sagged 11.9 to 1,259.3
points.
</P>
<P>
Almost 1.7 percent was wiped off the bank index which plunged
109.0 points to 6,336.6.
</P>
<P>
Sector heavyweight National Australia Bank took most of the
heat, sliding 59 cents, or 2.46 percent, to 23.40 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank slipped 28 cents to 24.12 Australian
dollars, ANZ dropped 20 cents to 10.78 Australian dollars and
Westpac eased 8.4 cents to 9.936 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 638.63 million stocks traded for 2.49
billion Australian dollars (1.64 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Falling stocks outnumbered rising stocks 761 to 513, while 388
stocks remained steady. 
</P>
