<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian National Council on Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
 inaugurated a 13-member national council on privatization in
capital Abuja Thursday, setting the stage for the three-phase
divestiture of government share holdings in companies and
conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
The president said that to be affected in the first phase of
the divestiture are 11 companies involved in cement production,
oil marketing and banking and insurance, local media reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The subsequent phases would involve divestiture of share
holdings in hotels, the country's five assembly plants, the four
refineries, the monopolies in the sectors of electricity and
telecommunications and the national airline.
</P>
<P>
The government's privatization program had been suspended by
the last military government after allegations that it was being
rushed to reward cronies and retired military officers.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said the council, which includes the ministers of
finance, justice, industry and the governor of the Central Bank,
would help improve the performance of state-owned companies and
stanch losses incurred in subsidizing them.
</P>
<P>
The president estimated the country had lost about 1.4 billion
U.S. dollars every year to "poor services" rendered by the
national electricity monopoly and inefficient fuel distribution.
</P>
<P>
"This does not include the human sufferings and losses of lives
due to fuel shortages," Obasanjo said, re-echoing sentiments
contained in his first budget submitted to the national
legislature last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The president said citizens have "continued to be blighted by
poor performance" of the companies with performance ranging from
"low returns to outright national disgrace" in spite of
investments of about eight billion dollars in these companies.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the divestiture was intended to achieve the
quick recovery of the social life of the people, adding that the
exercise is expected to affect about 1,000 state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
The president pledged the exercise would be "comprehensive,
transparent and accountable," as the government recognized it as
the key to "reviving public utilities and foreign confidence" in
the economy, prostrate from years of mismanagement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
