<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 S. African Miners Killed in Underground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen miners have been
confirmed dead in an underground explosion in Mponeng gold mine
southwest of Johannesburg on Thursday evening, local media
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
About 20 specially-trained rescue workers, who had been working
since the explosion at 6:00 p.m. Thursday, found the eighteenth
body before dawn Friday, South African Press Association (SAPA)
said.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers Friday morning were still looking for "any other
 casualties or survivors," but by mine owner Anglogold's reckoning
there was only one person left unaccounted for, Anglogold
spokesman James Duncan was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We will keep on going flat-out until we are satisfied everyone
is accounted for," Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty miners were lifted to safety Thursday night after the
explosion on 99 level, some 2,700 meters below surface. None of
the 20 were injured.
</P>
<P>
Duncan said the accident occurred as a dangerous gas --
probably methane -- ignited when the men were lengthening a major
access tunnel to a working area.
</P>
<P>
"They detected methane, the alert was given and the evacuation
was underway when the gas ignited."
</P>
<P>
It was unknown what had caused the gas to ignite.
</P>
<P>
He said the 18 men did nothing out of the ordinary and did not
deviate from safety procedures.
</P>
<P>
South African President Thabo Mbeki said in the early hours of
Friday that he was shocked and saddened to learn of the miners'
deaths and expressed his hope that no stone would be left unturned
to determine the exact cause of the disaster, and to determine
whether safety standards were adhered to.
</P>
<P>
"The president extends his heart-felt condolences to bereaved
family members, friends and colleagues," Mbeki's spokesman Ronnie
Mamoepa said before sunrise Friday.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's accident is the worst mining disaster in the history
of Anglogold, the world's biggest gold producer, since 1995 when
104 people were killed in the Vaal Reefs mine west of Johannesburg
when an underground lift plummeted down the mine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
