<HEADLINE> S. Africa Accused of Trying to Measure Force With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Angola Defense Minister Kundi
Payama accused South Africa of trying to measure its force with
Angola, the official Angolan news agency Angop reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa takes us for a rival," Payama said, adding that
there doesn't exist any confidence and solidarity between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Payama noted that South Africa regards Angola as main
competitor for regional leadership in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
With regard to South Africa's contribution to efforts to end
the civil war in Angola, Payama said that Angola received little
support from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that South Africa should make effort to
eliminate its hostility toward Angola.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that South Africa, eager to play a major role in
the on- going civil war in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC), considered that Angola had the advantage.
</P>
<P>
There is no immediate comment from Johannesburg on the Angolan
defense minister's speech.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the civil war in the DRC, Angola and South
Africa have different points of view. Angola sent its troops to
support the legal government led by DRC President Laurent Kabila
while South Africa has been urging the warring parties to
negotiate.
</P>
<P>
Payama also criticized Zambia of supporting Jonas Savimbi,
leader of the rebels National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA), which Lusaka has denied. 
</P>
