<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dovish Israeli Minister Objects to Syrian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- A dovish Israeli minister said
Friday that the Israeli-Syrian talks can not be resumed if Syria
insists on an Israeli commitment to a full withdrawal from the
Golan Heights as the precondition, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin, an architect of the historic
Oslo peace accords between Israel and the Palestinians, told the
radio that Israel's former Labor governments did not agree to
such a precondition in previous talks with Syria, which broke off
in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Syria insists that former Israeli governments of prime
ministers Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres had agreed in
negotiations to hand over the whole Golan Heights, a Syrian
plateau seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war, and
demanded that the talks be resumed from where they left off.
</P>
<P>
Winning a landslide in the premiership race in the May
election, Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged to revive the
peace process both on the Palestinian and Syrian tracks, largely
frozen in the three years of rule by his hard-line predecessor
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
He has said that he is ready to make necessary territorial
compromises for reaching a comprehensive peace, but has not make
clear to what extent he is prepared to withdraw from the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
His top foreign policy advisers have said that Israel would
agree to pick up the talks from the point where they broke off,
but stressed that it has different interpretation of what the
point is.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Minister without portfolio Haim Ramon also voiced
doubts over the resumption of talks if Syria did not show
flexibility, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy urged the United States Friday to
intensify its efforts to help restart the Israeli negotiations
with Syria as well as with the Palestinians, expressing hope that
a shuttle mission by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
next month would spur progress.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton urged Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad in a letter this week to seize the opportunity for peace
offered by Barak's election victory.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, Barak and Assad have exchanged messages
on the resumption of talks through third-party mediators.
Calling the messages "encouraging," Levy urged Damascus to move
beyond verbal signals by opening direct negotiations with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Arab Israeli legislator Azmi Bishara
will go to Syria via Amman Saturday for talks with Assad, Israel
Radio said. A delegation of 13 Arab Israeli legislators is
expected to visit Damascus in the near future, the radio
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
