<HEADLINE> Nigeria Unfolds Agenda to Revive Power, Steel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Power and Steel Minister
Ajibola Ige has unfolded a phased revival agenda for the low
efficient power and steel sectors in the west African country with
a promise to eliminate incidents of public power failure within
24 months.
</P>
<P>
The minister also listed on Thursday 10-point strategies to
salvage the embattled steel and aluminium sectors, threatening to
sack officials who fail to meet set targets, the Guardian
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ige, who put the implementation of the agenda in phases of six,
12 and 24 months, said he would adopt "a missionary approach to
management, not just to clear away the debris of past errors and
to prevent new blunders, but to build up structures and procedures
that would make strategic achievements difficult to reverse."
</P>
<P>
The targets for the power sector, according to the minister,
were to "cut down incidents of wanton power failures by 50 percent
in six months, by 75 percent in 12 months and by almost 100
percent in 24 months.
</P>
<P>
"No excuses will be accepted or acceptable. Meet target or be
fired," he added, hinting at his determination to sort out the
problems in the long- neglected sectors.
</P>
<P>
"The government is determined to put an end to the criminal
destruction of Nigeria Electric Power Authority (NEPA)'s
facilities, some of which border on sabotage. Henceforth, any
person, acting alone or in collusion with NEPA staff, found
guilty of tampering with electric plants, fittings or towers will
serve jail terms without an option of fine," said the minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
