<HEADLINE> 8 PKK Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Eight rebels of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) were killed in the military
operations in the past week in southeastern Turkey, an official
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by the office of the Emergency Regional
Rule, said that the Turkish security forces had wiped out two PKK
militants in Kulp town of Diyarbakir province, two in Beytussebap
town of Sirnak province, two in Semdinli province of Hakkari and
two in Tunceli province.
</P>
<P>
However, four Turkish soldiers also died in the armed clashes
between the PKK and the Turkish security forces in the region,
the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels have been fighting since 1984 a war for an
independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. The fighting
continues after PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan was sentenced to death
by Turkey's Ankara State Security Court last month.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts between the PKK and the security forces have claimed
over 37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
