<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Enlarge Broadcasting Network in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique plans to set up seven
community radio broadcasting stations and television stations in
seven provinces as part of efforts to enlarge the broadcasting
network in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Mozambican Association of Rural Development,
Joao Carrilho, said each station will cost some 100,000 U.S.
dollars, the Noticias newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
These stations can both receive and transmit radio and
television signals, covering an area of 30 square kilometers,
Carrilho said.
</P>
<P>
The stations will be located in the seven communities: Chimoio
of Manica Province, Cuamba of Niassa Province, Namiale of Nampula
Province, Gurue of Zambezia Province, Uingue of Tete Province,
Chiure of Cabo Delgado Province and Marromeu of Sofala Province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Mozambican Association of Community
Communications, with the help of international organizations like
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), has planned to set up 21
radio broadcasting stations in several counties across the country
by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
So far, four stations have been in operation in Maputo, Gaza,
Zambezia and Tete.
</P>
<P>
The first community broadcasting station began to operate in
Xai-Xai, capital of Gaza Province, three years ago financed by the
UNICEF. It covers an area of some 100 square kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
