<HEADLINE> World Leaders Open Second-Day Sarajevo Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sarajevo, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari opened the second-day summit of Stability Pact on Friday
here, at which leaders from major western countries are discussing
the post-crisis reconstruction in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
In an opening speech, chair of Bosnia and Herzegovina
presidency, Ante Jelavic said the stability pact to be adopted by
the summit will enable all the countries in the region to join
euro-atlantic integrations, particularly the European Union and
the Partnership for Peace, "which are our absolute priorities".
</P>
<P>
"I also think that today's inauguration of the Stability Pact
will immutably change the way of communication between the
countries in the region, as well as the global attitude toward the
region of southeastern Europe," Jelavic said.
</P>
<P>
"This new mode of cooperation and a strong integration
demension will permanently end the cycle of brutal conflicts that
have characterized the region so far," he added.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which constitutes part of the "stability pact" for
southeastern Europe, involves the 15 European Union (EU) member
states, nine non-EU European countries, the United States, Canada
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Also the current EU president, Ahtisaari told Balkan leaders
Thursday at the first-day summit that he hope this meeting
promotes constructive brainstorming about how to implement the
three aspects of the stability pact: democracy and human rights,
economic reconstruction, development and cooperation, and security
issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
