<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Coverage Up in Central China's Tourist Attraction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Forest coverage in Zhangjiajie,
the famous tourist attraction in central China's Hunan Province,
has jumped to 63.7 percent from 40 percent ten years ago, with the
forest coverage in its scenic spots soaring to over 97 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiajie, in northwestern Hunan, was approved by the State
Council in 1982 as the first national forest park in China, and
its Wulingyuan scenic spot was incorporated into the World
Heritage List by UNESCO in 1992.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Zhangjiajie Forest Bureau said that since
1988 when the city was established, Zhangjiajie has afforested an
area of 150,000 hectares, planted more than 50 million trees and
sealed off 220,000 hectares of mountains for afforestation.
</P>
<P>
The five nature reserves in the city, including one at state
level and three at provincial level, cover a total area of over 1,
000 square kilometers and are home to more than 4,000 species of
plants and wild animals, of which, over 3,000 species are high-
class plants and 75 are rare plant species under the state
protection.
</P>
<P>
He said that Zhangjiajie is striving to raise the city's forest
coverage to 67 percent by afforesting an additional area of 2,300
hectares and sealing off additional 3,300 hectares of mountains
for afforestation on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence that the '99 China Eco-Tour
International Forest Protection Festival, to be held in
Zhangjiajie September 20 to 27, will further increase public
awareness of forest protection and spur the afforestation efforts
in the city.
</P>
<P>
The Festival, whose theme is " Man and Nature, Fusion of Nature
and Culture", is sponsored by the National Tourism Administration,
State Forestry Administration, the Chinese Academy of Sciences and
Hunan Provincial Government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Strengthens Pharmacy Administration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
introduced new prescription pads and stamps in some big hospitals
nation-wide to curb drug pilfering, media reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"A particular stamp for a given hospital cannot be used at
another hospital. It's a way of curbing drug wastage in hospital
countrywide." Zambian Health Minister Nkandu Luo told the press in
Lusaka Thursday
</P>
<P>
Doctors and other medical practitioners in Zambian state-run
hospitals have been banned from prescribing drugs outside their
designated places of work.
</P>
<P>
The health minister expressed her worry about the shortage of
drugs in hospitals despite adequate stocks being supplied.
</P>
<P>
She admitted that there were flaws in the current distribution
of drugs nationwide, alleging that some medical practitioners had
taken advantage of the laxity in the prescription system to use
government-procured drugs for their own selfish needs.
</P>
<P>
Luo said that her ministry has introduced specific stamps for
various hospitals to control and limit cross-breed of
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
The move will be carried out as a pilot project at some
hospitals in the southern African country, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
