<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to End Fishing Ban in South China Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 30 (Xinhua) -- China will end the first fishing
ban imposed on the South China Sea area as of 24:00 tomorrow,
according to the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The fishing ban, which started on June 1, involves more than 30,
000 boats and one million fishermen, including some 1,800 boats
from Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
In the past two months, only seven boats were found fishing
illegally in the South China Sea, said Liu Guojun, who is in
charge of the fishing ban in the area.
</P>
<P>
The government has offered some subsidies to the fishermen who
had difficulty in making both ends meet as a result of the fishing
ban, Liu said, adding that the supply and prices of seafood
remained stable during the period thanks to the adequate store of
seafood and pelagic fishing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
