<HEADLINE> Leaders Discuss Post-Crisis Reconstruction in Sarajevo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sarajevo, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from major western
countries are gathering here Friday to join their counterparts of
the Balkan nations to discuss post-crisis reconstruction in
southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and other senior American officials
arrived here this morning among other world leaders to attend the
"Stability Pact Summit".
</P>
<P>
The summit, which constitutes part of the "stability pact" for
southeast Europe proposed by Germany, involves the 15 European
Union (EU) member states, nine non-EU European countries, the
United States, Canada and Japan. Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari chairs the gathering in the capital of Bosnia-
Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Also the current European Union president, Ahtisaari told
Balkan leaders Thursday at the first-day meeting that he hopes
this gathering will promote constructive brainstorming about how
to implement the three aspects of the stability pact: democracy
and human rights, economic reconstruction, development and
cooperation, and security issues.
</P>
<P>
The second day of the summit is aimed to reinforce the
political importance of the stability pact agreed by the major
western powers in June to consider the long-term future of the
region after the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
