<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environment Assessment Required of HK's Major Theme Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Major theme parks and amusement
parks in Hong Kong are required to evaluate their potential
impacts on the environment under an amendment to the existing
legislation.
</P>
<P>
The Environmental Impact Assessment Order 1999 published in a
government gazette Friday provides for the inclusion of theme
parks and amusement parks with a site area of more than 20
hectares as designated projects, the construction or operations of
which will require an environmental permit.
</P>
<P>
Taking immediate effect, the amendment order makes it necessary
for such parks to take prevention and mitigation measures to
protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Planning, Environment and Lands Bureau
explained that the adoption of 20 hectares as the site size
threshold is consistent with the present schedules of the
ordinance.
</P>
<P>
Small theme parks or amusement parks are unlikely to cause
significant adverse environmental impact under normal
circumstances, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The amendment order will be implemented through the existing
approval and enforcement arrangements under the Environmental
Impact Assessment Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is in negotiation with Walt Disney corporation on the
possibility of construction of a Disney theme park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Jobless Rate Hits New Record High in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Japan's unemployment rate hit a new
record high of 4.9 percent in June, with the rate for men reaching
an all-time high of 5.1 percent, the Management and Coordination
Agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted jobless rate in June went up 0.3
percentage points from the previous month's level, the highest
since the Japanese government began compiling employment data in
1953, the agency said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate followed 4.6 percent in May and the previous
record high of 4.8 percent registered in both March and April, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
The June jobless rate for men went up 0.2 percentage points
from the level in May, while the figure for women also rose 0.2
percentage point to 4.4 percent, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
The number of workers who were forced to leave their jobs
reached a record high of 1.18 million, far more than the 1.03
million who quit by themselves, it said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Japan's Labor Ministry said in a separate
report that the ratio of job offers to job seekers remained at a
record low of 0.46 for the second straight month in June on a
seasonally adjusted basis. The ratio means there were only 46 job
offers for every 100 job seekers.
</P>
<P>
"Considering the jobless rate and the offer-seeker ratio, the
country's employment situation is becoming increasingly severe,"
the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
