<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches Energy Efficiency Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Friday launched a
four-year industrial energy efficiency improvement project to
address the problem of inefficient and wasteful use of energy in
industrial facilities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The project at a cost of 80 million ringgit (about 21.052
million U.S. dollars) has targeted eight energy-intensive
industrial sub-sectors -- cement, ceramics, foodstuff, glassware,
iron and steel, pulp and paper, rubber and wood-based industries.
</P>
<P>
Launching the project here, Energy, Communications and
Multimedia Minister Leo Moggie said the project would focus on
promoting industrial energy efficiency using specific programs
that would facilitate voluntary initiatives on the part of the
industries.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Malaysian government was also studying
the option of introducing appropriate economic measures for energy
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The project to be implemented by the newly-established Malaysia
Energy Center is part of global efforts by the Global Environment
Facility (GEF) to mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions. The GEF
serves as the interim financial mechanism body for the UN
Framework Convention on Climate Change.
</P>
<P>
It was envisaged that by the year 2004, GHG emissions from the
eight sub-sectors in Malaysia would see a decrease of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The project has received a grant of 29 million ringgit (about
7.631 million U.S. dollars) from the GEF and the United Nations
Development Program.
</P>
<P>
A national steering committee has been formed to monitor the
progress in the implementation of the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Prevent Total Foreign Participation in Restructuring: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will prevent complete
foreign involvement in restructuring and avoid selling assets
cheap, Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda said here on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Although foreign participation in the restructuring in Thailand
may be positive, Thailand is adjusting its system to avoid
complete foreign involvement, Tarrin told reporters when attending
the conference "Back to the Basics?".
</P>
<P>
World Bank chief economist Joseph Stiglitz cautioned Thailand
on Wednesday that a rush to sell off local banks to foreign
players might turn out to be simply giving away domestic assets on
the cheap, especially at a time of recovery.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister pointed out that restructuring is really
important for the Thai economy to emerge stronger, adding that the
authorities will review the economic growth target soon.
</P>
<P>
He said the Thai economy is recovering as fast as it can. The
Thai government has already retargeted the growth rate from one
percent early this year to 1.2-1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We are quite certain that we'll possibly grow this year," he
said.
</P>
<P>
When talking about the issue of non-performing loans (NPLs),
the minister said the NPL levels in Thai banks are relatively
stable now. NPLs in the Thai banking sector account for 47 percent
of total loans.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand and other authorities are urging the
sector to solve this problem as quickly as they can, Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has so far closed or intervened in 70
finance companies and banks and is now in the process of
privatizing four commercial banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
