<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Caffeine Good for Small Babies: Researchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AAP Friday reported that a study funded by the National Health
and Medical Research Council found that intravenous doses of
caffeine stimulates that part of the brain which signals the lungs
to inflate.
</P>
<P>
Dr Bruce Charles, from the University of Queensland's school of
pharmacy, was quoted as saying premature babies who suffered the
breathing problem, known as apnoea, also had problems eliminating
drugs.
</P>
<P>
The one currently used, theophylline, can cause the heart to
race and may lead to gastrointestinal problems, whereas caffeine
has none of these drawbacks.
</P>
<P>
"I've been interested in the way drugs are eliminated by these
babies because they have such tiny immature kidneys and livers
they have huge problems getting rid of drugs," Charles said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years Charles has studied 250 babies at
Brisbane's Mater Mothers' Hospital who have relied on a mechanical
ventilator to breathe because of apnoea.
</P>
<P>
Apnoea starves the blood of oxygen which can lead to brain
damage and death.
</P>
<P>
The study is the first to use caffeine for apnoea and has
attracted international attention.
</P>
<P>
"We expect it (caffeine) will be the drug which will replace
the current ones as a result of this study." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
