<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Passenger Car Sales Increase Sharply in 1st Half 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Passenger car sales in
Malaysia rose by 107 percent in the first six months of this year,
4
according to the Malaysian Motor Traders Association (MMTA)
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sales during the period under review amounted to 106,840 units
against 51,605 units in the corresponding period 1998, MMTA said,
expecting a even better second half year performance.
</P>
<P>
MMTA said passenger car sales are expected to reach 215,000
units this year, an increase of 56 percent over 1998 when a total
of 137,691 passenger cars were sold.
</P>
<P>
It forecast that total sales of vehicles, covering commercial
vehicles and four-wheel drive vehicles also, for the whole of this
year would rise to 260,000 units from an earlier forecast of
200,000 units against total vehicle sales of 163,151 units for
1998.
</P>
<P>
Increased vehicle sales point to an improving economy under the
current economic backdrop as vehicle sales are often used as a
yardstick to measure the state of the economy.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months of this year, national car sales
totaled 98,349 units against 47,416 units in the same period of
last year, up by 107 percent, MMTA said.
</P>
<P>
Proton, Malaysia's major passenger car manufacturer, selling
70,126 units in the January-June period this year, accounted for
66 percent of the total passenger car market, against 31,232 units
in the same period 1998 or 60.5 percent of total passenger car
market, according to MMTA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
