<HEADLINE> Osama Desires to Leave Afghanistan: Sources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden
has expressed his desire to leave Afghanistan fearing an imminent
U.S. attack, sources close to Osama and the Taliban told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban have endorsed Osama's decision to leave the
war-torn country, but insisted they would not force him to leave,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to increase the difficulties for Afghanistan and
its people by staying in the country," the sources quoted Osama as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi dissident, who is most wanted by the United States
for his alleged terrorist activities, said that he had started
searching for a suitable new place to go.
</P>
<P>
If he receives any invitation from any Islamic country, he will
proceed there, said Osama.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Taliban militia have promised to facilitate
Osama in shifting to any other country.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban authorities announced that Osama was missing in
February this year. However, a Taliban spokesman admitted on July
8 that the 41-year-old Saudi dissident was still in Afghanistan
after the U.S. announcement of imposing economic sanctions against
the Taliban for his support to Osama.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's supreme leader Mulla Omar last week rejected the
U.S. demand for Osama's extradition from Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The United States launched missile attacks on the alleged
terrorist bases in Afghanistan run by Osama in August last year.
</P>
<P>
Osama was blamed for masterminding car bomb blasts at the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania last August in which more than 200
people, including 12 Americans, were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
