<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Raise Cashew Nut Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania aims to raise its
cashew nut production to 110,000 tons in this year, the Ministry
of Agriculture and Cooperatives has said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said this in a budget report presented to the
National Assembly earlier this month, Business Times reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the demand of cashew nuts in the world market is
high as Vietnam, one of the leading exporters, has less yields.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's processing plants are running short of raw nuts and
have to buy from other producers like Cote d'Ivoire and
Mozambique, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that prices of cashew kernels -- processed nuts
removed from their shells, have jumped to 3.2 U.S. dollars per
pound from 2.3 dollar per pound in January this year.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's cashew nut output in 1998/99 (from June 30, 1998 to
July 1, 1999) rose to 105,000 tons from 93,200 tons in the
previous year with the increase of prices of the crop in the world
market.
</P>
<P>
The Cashew Nut Association of Tanzania has said it will make
joint efforts with the government and farmers in raising the
cashew nut output.
</P>
<P>
With funds from the World Bank, Tanzania plans to improve the
processing capacity of the crop in the major growing areas along
the Indian Ocean coastal belt comprising Tanga, Coast, Lindi and
Mtwara regions.
</P>
<P>
The improvement program involves spraying pesticides to treat
"powder mildew" disease at the right time as well as proper crop
husbandry.
</P>
<P>
Cashew nut production has shown marked increase in the past
five years. In 1993/94, output stood at only 46,600 tons.
</P>
<P>
As one of the traditional cash crops, cashew nut is a source of
 livelihood for an estimated 300,000 families, who tend about 30
million trees on 4,000 hectares of land.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Magazine Repudiates Falun Gong Fallacies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although Li advocates truthfulness, what he has done is just
the opposite. His books are written by ghostwriters, his date of
birth was falsified to coincide with that of Sakyamuni, the
founder of Buddhism (565 B.C.-486 B.C.), and he saw doctors and
took medicines himself but told other not to do so.
</P>
<P>
As for benevolence, Li boasts that Falun Gong can convert
people, but he refused to recruit those people who were fatally
ill to his Falun Gong classes. Some Falun Gong practitioners lost
their lives just because of a refusal to see doctors or take any
medicines, whereas others comitted suicide when they tried to
locate the "Dharma Wheel" inside their own bodies. Where's the
benevolence in this? it queries.
</P>
<P>
Although he preached tolerance, Li and his followers have never
shown much tolerance themselves. They wouldn't put up with
criticism or opposition, it says, and for several months, Falun
Gong practitioners have harassed or threatened the people who had
different views and attacked at news organizations and even Party
and government headquarters, seriously disrupting the public order.
</P>
<P>
All this shows that Li Hongzhi is neither truthful, benevolent,
nor tolerant and that behind these three main tenets of the Falun
Gong, there exist nasty political motives. If unchecked, Li and
his followers will do great harms to the state and society, it
stresses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
