<HEADLINE> Horticultural Exports Earn Kenya $103M in 1st Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenya earned 7.4 billion shillings
(around 103 million U.S. dollars) from exports of fresh
horticultural produce in the first six months of this year, a 68
percent increase over the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director Martin Mulandi of the country's Horticultural
Crops Development Authority said here Thursday that the volume of
crops export rose by 58 percent to 56,633 tons in the six-month
period from 35,840 tons for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Friday quoted Mulandi as
saying that exports of cut flowers went up by 24 percent to 19,283
tons, fruits by 87 percent to 11,998 tons and vegetables by 83
percent to 25,352 tons.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the increase of crop exports to the
rehabilitation of Nairobi-Mombasa highway which is the only outlet
to the seaport city of Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Mulandi said this year's total value and volume of
horticultural exports are expected to surpass 14.38 billion
shillings (some 197 million dollars) and 231,067 tons recorded in
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
