<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Should Enhance Anti-drug Campaign: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government should
take comprehensive measures to stamp out drug menace, a senior
anti-drug official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jewel Canson, head of the National Drug Law Enforcement
Prevention and Coordination Center, said the plan should combine
the forces of law-making, law enforcement and educational campaign
in fighting the illegal drug scourge.
</P>
<P>
The illegal drug trade in the nation was estimated to have
reached 250 billion pesos (6.2 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998
alone, and some 1.7 million Filipinos have fallen victim to drug
addiction.
</P>
<P>
Canson said the government needs stronger legislation that
would give more muscles to the government's anti-drug efforts.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need for specialized courts to handle drug
offense along with a specialized prosecution service for trial of
these cases.
</P>
<P>
A more effective way to treat and rehabilitate drug abuses is
also in need, Canson said, citing the "growing number" of young
people hooked to prohibited substances.
</P>
<P>
Preventive education, support and cooperation of Filipinos from
all walks of life are also important in the campaign against drug
abuse and trafficking, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the drug scourge will destroy the future of young
Filipinos if no tougher measures are adopted to curb the menace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
