<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Moody's Investors Service, one of
the world's leading rating agencies, today signed an co-operative
agreement with a Chinese rating firm, the Dagong Global Credit
Rating Co., Ltd.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, their co-operation will come into
two phases. In the first phase, the two sides will jointly develop
a rating system tailored to China's domestic capital market. And
Moody's will offer assistance to Dagong in credit analysis, credit
research and crediting training but will not be involved in the
rating of any specific projects.
</P>
<P>
In the second phase, they will form a joint venture when the
time is mature.
</P>
<P>
Moody's President John Rutherfurd said the agreement "comes at
a good time for both organizations, as well as for China, whose
rapidly-growing economy has created a large demand for education
and training in credit risks and analysis."
</P>
<P>
"China's growth potential, Dagong's position in the market, and
Moody's century-old reputation as the most trusted name in credit
analysis should provide for a very constructive co-operation," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jizhong, chairman of the Dagong, said, "It is the desire of
all countries around the world to still more effectively analyze
and manage financial risk in a bid to maintain financial integrity,
and this co-operation with Moody's will assist Dagong in playing
an important role in serving the domestic markets in the People's
Republic."
</P>
<P>
Noting that China's rating agencies are still relatively young,
he said that co-operation with international rating agencies would
help narrow the gap between the country's rating agencies and
their international counterpart and would allow them to play a
still bigger role in protecting investors' interests, disclosing
and reducing financial risks and promoting the growth of the
Chinese capital market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
