<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Group Saying Good-bye To Out-of-date Farming Methods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Yao ethnic group in China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has abandoned its older farming
methods of burning off the mountainside and has begun using more
ecologically-sound farming techniques.
</P>
<P>
The land-locked Yao villages are often poor and the people
there used to develop farmland by burning off the growth on
mountainsides for simple farming. Zhao Wenxing, of Jinxiu County,
for example, says that his family moved three times to make room
for this massive burning technique.
</P>
<P>
But, things began to change when more modern methods were
introduced after China's reforms in 1978. And, because logging and
the burning of forests were banned in the 1980s in the Dayao
Mountains, where many Yao people live, forest coverage has
increased to some 73 percent from 39 percent and fir and fruit
trees and spice bushes now cover the mountain slopes.
</P>
<P>
Anise is one spice being planted on the hillsides in Jinxiu and
it brought in 30 million yuan in export earnings last year. It is
a popular product in Hong Kong, Japan, and France.
</P>
<P>
In Bama, a Yao autonomous county, farmers have just said good-
bye to their small huts that dotted the mountains and some 3,400
households have moved into larger buildings. In Gongcheng County,
people have also given up the old habit of using straw and tree
branches for fuel and are using cleaner energy like marsh gas and
70 percent of the farmers have marsh gas pits in their courtyards.
</P>
<P>
The fruit they produce are "green products", because they use
decomposed straws from marsh gas pits, instead of chemicals, to
fertilize their fruit trees, says Liu Yumin, one local farmer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
