<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Foreign Auto Giants Expand Business in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- With demands in India's
automotive industry showing signs of an uptrend, foreign auto
giants have expanded their business presence in India.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, Ford Motor Company of the United States and
Fiat Spa of Italy signed an agreement to study the possibility of
jointly manufacturing engines and other auto components for their
respective future vehicles designed for India.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement signed Wednesday in Turin, Italy,
the two companies will explore the possible use of Fiat India Auto
Ltd's plant in Mumbai, as a proposed joint engine production site.
</P>
<P>
The study, which is expected to be completed by the end of the
year, will cover engines of small- and mid-sized cars planned for
India by both the companies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japanese car giant Toyota is planning to introduce a
mid-sized car in India to cater to the needs of the growing
middle-class market and will consider introducing the passenger
car by 2004-2005.
</P>
<P>
Sachio Yamazaki, managing director of Toyota Kirloskar, said
Thursday, "The preference for the small cars in the country at
present is a compromise choice because of price factor and an
average middle class family really needs a mid-sized car."
</P>
<P>
As real income grows, the demand for bigger cars is expected to
increase, he added.
</P>
<P>
Toyota Kirloskar, which is an 87:13 joint venture between
Toyota and Kirloskars, also signed a memorandum of understanding
Wednesday with the Directorate General of Foreign Trade for
importing 544 million U.S. dollars worth of auto components in 5
years.
</P>
<P>
The company has already made an investment of 6 billion rupees
(140 million U.S. dollars) in the Indian venture and targets to
sell 31,000 vehicles in the first year of its operation.
</P>
<P>
Trial production of a multi-purpose vehicle for private and
commercial use has already began and commercial production is
likely to begin by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Hoping to get back on the profit track, Sekurit Saint-Gobain,
an 18 billion U.S. dollar industrial conglomerate of France, has
hiked its equity stake in its Indian arm Sekurit Saint-Gobain
India from 51 percent to 75.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the issue is to part-finance the new project
in Pune with a capacity to produce 2.4 million pieces of
tough-ended safety glasses for window and back glasses per annum
for the automotive industry.
</P>
<P>
The company has already started negotiations with new companies
which have set up manufacturing bases in India and are presently
importing their toughened safety glass requirements to sell its
products.
</P>
<P>
According to the Society of Indian Automobile Association,
sales of commercial vehicles went up by 24 percent to 31,834 units
in the first quarter of the current fiscal year ended in June, as
against 25,618 units sold in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Among them, the medium and heavy commercial segment saw a 44
percent increase in market with sales going up to 19,397 units as
against 13,470 units in the same period last fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
