<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mausoleum Of Xixia Emperor Now Open To Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The excavation site of the
mausoleum of the Xixia emperor in northwest China is open to the
public and is expected to attract a considerable number of
tourists.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists in charge of the excavation say that cemetery No.
3 has quite a number of valuable cultural relics, one of the most
outstanding of which is a stele in the form of a statue 140
centimeters high with a decorated face.
</P>
<P>
The site also has parts of steles engraved with characters,
three pedestals for stone statues, decorated bricks, porcelain
shards, coins, bronzeware, iron tools, and building adornments.
</P>
<P>
The Ningxia Archeology Research Institute began excavating the
site in August and September last year and the State Cultural
Heritage Administration calls some of the findings the most
important for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Xixia was established in what is modern-day Ningxia in the 11th
century and was inhabited by a number of ethnic groups. It was
then conquered by the Yuan Dynasty in 1227. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
