<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Archipelago Becomes Part Of World Biosphere Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Nanji Islands marine nature
reserve, an archipelago off the southern tip of east China's
Zhejiang Province, has become a member of the World Biosphere
Network of UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
The 200-sq.km. reserve in the East China Sea is China's first
marine area to belong to the network. A recent survey found that
it is home to 421 types of mollusks, 633 species of algae, 397
types of fish, and 257 types of crustaceans, as well as 157 other
marine forms. Many of the species are unique to this part of the
world.
</P>
<P>
The Nanji Islands were listed as the first level-five marine
nature reserve in 1990 and the archipelago became a member of the
China Biosphere Nature Reserve Network in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Province approved its Nanji Islands Protection
Regulations in 1996 and plans to set up an ecology monitoring
station in the near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
