<HEADLINE> U.S. Gunman Kills Himself After Killing 12 People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 29 (Xinhua) -- An investor upset over stock
trading losses opened fire Thursday in two brokerage offices in
Atlanta City, Georgia State, killing nine people and wounding 12
others before escaping, and then killed himself when stopped by
police.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the gunman's wife and two children were found beaten
to death in their suburban home.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell said the gunman, Mark Barton, 44,
committed suicide after police cornered him in a dark green van at
a service station in Atlanta's northern suburbs about five hours
after the office shootings.
</P>
<P>
"He was pulled over, and then killed himself," Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
Two handguns were found at the scene and notes were found with
the family members' bodies, he said.
</P>
<P>
Barton, a chemist, walked into a brokerage office at Securities
Center in downtown Atlanta about 3 p.m. (2100 GMT), opened fire,
then walked across the street and began shooting at another
brokerage firm, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
Four of the victims were killed in one building and five in the
other, he said.
</P>
<P>
Campbell said U.S. Vice President Al Gore had telephoned to
offer condolences and federal assistance in coping with the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
It was the latest in a grim wave of mass shootings at schools
and workplaces and was among the worst office massacres ever in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta was one of several cities in the United States to sue
gun manufacturers, seeking to recoup the costs of gun-related
violence. But the state legislature, heavily lobbied by the
National Rifle Association, swiftly passed a law prohibiting such
suits.
</P>
<P>
Georgia law requires no state permit to buy or own a gun but
does require a permit to carry a concealed weapon, according to
the National Rifle Association Web site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
