<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese PM Calls for Y2K Prevention Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van
Khai urged all the country's administrative and economic sectors
to finish the plans to prevent the Y2K problem before November 15,
1999, Vietnam's English daily Vietnam News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In his message on July 28 to high-ranking government officials,
business leaders and heads of other organizations, Khai asked them
to solve key issues relating to the Y2K problem, give priority to
the repair and replacement of equipment and submit periodical
reports on the Y2K situation to the National Steering Committee
for the Year 2000 Computer Incident (Y2K) Prevention.
</P>
<P>
In his message, Khai also required that all tests to ensure the
defeat of the millennium bug must be done before Wednesday,
October 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's National Steering Committee for Y2K Prevention said
provincial people's committees and industrial departments have yet
to fully assess the possible impact of the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the sluggishness to a low awareness of the
potential difficulties among managers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
