<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Aviation Y2K Ready by October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Department of
Transportation and Communications has declared that the nation's
aviation sector will be Y2K compliant by this year, Manila
Standard newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Department Secretary Vicente Rivera told participants of the
First Y2K Aviation Forum that two months from now, the
navigational equipment of all the country's international airports
will be fully Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
Y2K, or the millennium bug problem, refers to fears that older
computer programs that count years by the last two digits may
mistaken 2000 for 1900, wreaking havoc on everything from airlines
to bank teller machines that run on computer.
</P>
<P>
Rivera said all the country's major airports, namely the Ninoy
Aquino International Airport, Mactan-Cebu International Airport,
Clark International Airport and Subic International Airport have
developed air traffic management Y2K contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
River said the department has allocated 55.6 million pesos to
the Air Transport Office (ATO) for the air sector's Y2K
preparations.
</P>
<P>
ATO's mainframe computer, called the automatic teletype message
switching computer system, has already been declared Y2K compliant
after a series of tests, Rivera added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
