<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Report Finding Sexual Differentiation 1.8 Billion Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Some Chinese scientists announced
today that sexual differentiation can be dated back at least 1.8
billion years, in sharp contrast to previous figures put at around
620 million years.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Shixing, of the Tianjin Geology Institute, came to this
conclusion with fellow researchers after analyzing some newly-
discovered fossilized algae from the Yan mountains in Hebei
Province.
</P>
<P>
When examined under microscope, the fossilized algae were found
to have sexual organs with a sperm sac and an egg sac and the
scientists have even discovered some sperm and eggs in the sac
after magnifying them 2,500 times with an electron microscope.
</P>
<P>
The fossils were buried in a rock layer of the early
Proterozoic period, Zhu says, and these are the earliest sexual
organs ever found and the finding is encouraging because it helps
explain how life evolved.
</P>
<P>
Sexual differentiation made the reproduction of living things
more complex and increased their genetic information and provided
the potential for evolution, according to Zhang Yun, a biologist
at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that for a long period of time after life
forms emerged on earth some four billion years ago, the highest
form of life consisted of only single-cell organisms that had no
sexual differentiation, something like the amoeba in modern times.
</P>
<P>
Before this new discovery, the only reliable evidence for
sexual reproduction of multicell organisms was the 620 million-
year-old fossils of multicellular plants with indications of
sexual organs that were discovered in 1996 by Beijing University
scientists.
</P>
<P>
Many scientists have guessed that sexual reproduction occurred
around two billion years ago, but they haven't been able to find
any concrete evidence. And a few scientists are skeptical about
the new discovery. Xing Shengyu, a former curator of the China
Geology Museum, says he can not believe it because it is very
difficult to identify the fossilized structure of plants that are
so old.
</P>
<P>
But Zhu insists that his group have used solid methods to
examine the fossils and rock samples and have been very careful in
drawing their conclusion.
</P>
<P>
A panel of paleontologists and geologists from the Chinese
Academy of Sciences have examined Zhu's research results, which
appeared in today's Chinese Science Bulletin, the most
authoritative academic natural science journal in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
