<HEADLINE> Guatemala's Economy Grows 3 Percent in First Half of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Guatemala's economy in the
first half of 1999 grew by three percent over the same period last
year, central bank president Edin Velazquez said Thursday,
according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Velazquez said the country's economy has had "a quite
satisfactory global result" in the first half of this year, in
spite of the difficult international situation.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the government target of 3.9
percent growth of the gross domestic product (GDP) for 1999 will
be attained.
</P>
<P>
However, the Bank of Guatemala noted negative performances in
the country's exports, citing a 48.5 percent slide in the earnings
of coffee exports in the first half of 1999 compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Another factor darkening the horizon is the growth of the
government's internal debt, which went from about 844 million U.S.
dollars last December to 900 million dollars in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
