<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Clashes Claim 9 Lives in Batam, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 30 (Xinhua) -- Violent clashes between migrant
groups from Sumatera and Flores continued in Indonesia's Batam,
just 35 kilometers southeast of Singapore, on Thursday night,
claiming at least nine lives.
</P>
<P>
The Antara News Agency said nine were killed and seven others
seriously injured, mostly from sharp weapons. But Batam Police
chief Lt. Col. D.A. Wibawa confirmed 11 victims during the riot,
which erupted when drivers from the two ethnic groups quarreled as
they competed for passengers in Muka Kuning subdistrict on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Although Security Director of Batam Authority Brigadier General
Eric Wotulo has issued a shoot-on-sight order on Thursday,
residents preferred to stay indoors, Antara reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the initial clash between the two groups
of drivers broke out on Sunday, killing one in Buralimar areas. On
Monday, two more people were killed there.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people fled their homes following the violence,
with many of them now sheltered at the local police station.
</P>
<P>
"Shops closed and streets were deserted soon after today's
(Thursday) brawl," Hasan from the Riau Post said.
</P>
<P>
A meeting between representatives of the two ethnic groups and
the local administration on Thursday failed to reach a truce.
</P>
<P>
Batam authorities have appealed to the central government to
restrict the number of poorly educated migrants in the industrial
island, which is a half-hour boat ride from Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Batam is a special industrial zone and also a popular tourist
destination for Singaporeans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
