<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President Meets U.S. Top Anti-Drug Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. anti-drug czar Barry
McCaffrey met here Thursday with Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez
and discussed cooperation between their two countries in fighting
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, McCaffrey told reporters that he agreed with
Chavez that the anti-drug effort in the Western hemisphere could
be expanded into the field of combating money laundering
</P>
<P>
He expressed worries that Colombian criminal groups will make
incursions into the United States via Venezuela, the neighbor of
Colombia, which is the world's largest cocaine exporter.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. top anti-drug official, who arrived here Wednesday
evening for a two-day visit from Colombia, denied allegations by
the media that his country is using the war against local drug
dealers as a pretense to send troops to Colombia.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey said his country ruled out an intervention in the
countries of the Western hemisphere like Colombia, where there
exist internal armed conflicts between the government and
guerrilla groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
