<HEADLINE> Brazilian Truckers End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Transport Minister
Eliseu Padilha on Thursday announced the end of the transport
worker's national strike.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Brazilian authorities had expressed a
hope to end the four-day strike. They said the nationwide strike
and the road blocks caused gasoline and food shortages throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian truckers launched the strike on Monday demanding the
cancellation of price hikes on fuels and tolls. They also set up
road blocks in many major cities.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Brazilian President Fernando Cardoso convened
an emergency meeting of his ministers to tackle the crisis. The
president said he would use the army and the police to lift the
road blocks. The blocks on certain roads were causing serious
traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
The transport workers, however, allowed ambulances, firemen and
buses of foodstuff and fuels to pass unimpeded. 
</P>
