<HEADLINE> Italian Police Arrest Uranium Traffickers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Italian Police have tracked down an
international enriched uranium-trafficking ring and arrested more
than a dozen of its members in Rome and Palermo, capital of Sicily,
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In March 1998, policemen who disguised as uranium buyers
penetrated into the ring, leading to the recovery of one 10-
kilogram ingot of enriched uranium and the arrest of 15 suspects.
</P>
<P>
Further investigation showed that the group had stolen
altogether 10 ingots of enriched uranium, which were meant for
shipment from the United States to Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The police are searching for the other nine missing pieces.
</P>
<P>
Enriched uranium can easily be used in the production of
nuclear weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Hits Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 30 (Xinhua) -- The recent heat wave has turned
the Chinese capital into a sauna.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say that Beijing is having its hottest summer in
100 years, with temperatures reaching 42 degrees centigrade. An
egg can fry on the pavement in some places, people say.
</P>
<P>
The often noisy, bustling city has calmed down a bit and the
numbers of vehicles and pedestrians are half what they usually are.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say that this weather is a result of a high
pressure warm air mass that has been hovering over northern China.
Many people in Beijing have suffered heatstroke and some have even
died. The Beijing First-Aid Center says that more than 20 people
have been hospitalized and a 76-year-old man died of a stroke this
week. Big factories like the Beijing Iron and Steel Corporation
have installed more air-conditioners and provided health exams for
workers.
</P>
<P>
However, the heat has not dampened tourists' enthusiasm. One
retired military man from the southern city of Shenzhen said that
this was a rare chance for him and the weather could not stop him
from climbing up the Tiananmen Rostrum, which had been a big dream
of his.
</P>
<P>
Swimming pools, libraries, and grassy places are where some go
to escape the heat. The number of swimmers is five times that of
normal years and many people are going to air-conditioned bars and
theaters at night. The hot weather has done one good thing,
according to Meng Lu, an actress, it has enriched night life.
</P>
<P>
Police, garbage collectors, and bus drivers however can't take
the day off. Beijing's 5,000 buses and trolleys are continuing to
transport the 9 million urbanites daily.
</P>
<P>
The biggest beneficiaries may be refrigerator, air-conditioner,
and ice-cream sellers. Dahua Electric Appliance Company located in
northern Beijing has been selling an average of 50 air-
conditioners daily, twice its earlier sales figures.
</P>
<P>
There have been electricity shortages, and sources at the
Beijing Electricity Supply Bureau say that there are three times
the number of electrical problems that they had during the same
period last year. The bureau has had to send 1,000 people out for
emergency repairs.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say that rain is expected in the next few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
