<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "La Nina" Causes Lower Temperatures in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador and other South American
countries with coasts facing the Pacific Ocean are registering
temperatures below normal due to the climatic phenomenon of "La
Nina," experts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The lower temperatures in Ecuador, Colombia, Peru and Chile
contrast with the extremely high temperatures in other countries,
according to investigators from the Oceanographic Institute of the
Armed Forces (INOCAR) and the Permanent Commission of the South
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The "La Nina" phenomenon will last until October and will very
probably be more intense in the last quarter of the year, experts
affirmed.
</P>
<P>
The scientific investigation ship called the "Orion," which is
operated by Ecuador's army, detected last month the presence of
the Humboldt cold current facing the country's coasts.
</P>
<P>
"La Nina," in contrast with the climatic phenomenon "El Nino,"
causes a descent in temperatures and a reduction of rains on the
South American coast facing the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
According to investigators, trade winds have grown intense in
southern Ecuador, especially in the oceanic region of Guayaquil
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The air temperature in this zone fluctuates between 19.5
degrees centigrade toward the south and 25.5 toward the north.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990730.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 </DATE_TIME>
