<HEADLINE> World PC Market Up 26 percent in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 29 (Xinhua) -- The personal computer industry
received a boost in the second quarter this year as worldwide
shipments grew more than 26 percent over the same period of 1998,
according to two market reports issued this week.
</P>
<P>
U.S. research firms Dataquest and International Data
Corporation (IDC) reported very similar estimates of worldwide PC
shipments in the second quarter, between 25.3 million and 25.6
million units.
</P>
<P>
All regions of the world experienced strong PC shipment growth
during the past three months. Dataquest said that the growth was
driven by lower system prices, economic recovery and the Internet,
while IDC attributed the increase to strong consumer demand and
continued growth of the low-cost segment.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide volume growth was led by the United States, which
expanded a robust 35 percent to more than 10 million units in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Markets in Asia-Pacific, driven by a return in business
confidence together with Internet-related consumer PC demand,
continued to gain momentum.
</P>
<P>
Sales of commercial PCs in western Europe were healthy and
offset slowness in consumer demand throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
The Latin American market also did well as Brazil showed signs
of recovering from the exchange rate crisis in January.
</P>
<P>
Among major vendors, Compaq remained number one in the PC
market worldwide, with shipments of 3.7 million units and 14.6
percent of world market share. The rest of the top five vendors
were Dell, IBM, Hewlett-Packard and Gateway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
