Sports Minister to become a "special envoy" for England's bid to
get the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
He may also be planning to stand as Labour's candidate to
become the first directly-elected mayor of London, which would
mean taking on both Ken Livingstone and now Glenda Jackson.
</P>
<P>
The outspoken 54-year-old has been Sports Minister since the
1997 general election. He will join Sir Bobby Charlton and Sir
Geoff Hurst at the forefront of the attempt to bring the
tournament to England in 2006 for the first time since 1966.
</P>
<P>
England face stiff competition, notably from South Africa and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Football's world governing body FIFA will announce the
successful bidder in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
Germany received a boost in their bid earlier this month when
the man heading its bid to beat England was nominated by FIFA
president Sepp Blatter as his ideal successor.
</P>
<P>
Blatter is keen on the 2006 tournament being held in Africa -
which has never hosted the World Cup before - but his public
tribute to Franz Beckenbauer will be viewed in Germany as a boost
for their bid. 
</P>
