<HEADLINE> Fiat to Seek Allies From Position of Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 29 (Xinhua) -- Italian car-maker Fiat looks at any
future partnerships "from a position of strength," Fiat's Chairman
Paolo Fresco said to Italian media recently.
</P>
<P>
Fresco said to Italy's weekly "Panorama" in an interview to be
published Friday that the dominant Italian car-maker will in any
case "keep control of its own destiny."
</P>
<P>
"I guarantee that we are among the most active, perhaps the
most active at the moment in seeking opportunities for
acquisitions, alliances, mergers and other operations," the Fiat
boss said.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that since the start of the year Fiat has spent
more than 10 trillion lire ( about 5.5 billion U.S. dollars ) on
acquisitions such as the U.S. tractor firm of Case and the U.S.
engineering firm Pico.
</P>
<P>
As for Fiat's failure to buy Volvo of Sweden late last year,
Fresco said "it went wrong because there was too much talk about
it, too early."
</P>
<P>
Fiat suffered a reverse when its bid for the whole of Volvo,
including its truck division, was beaten by Ford's bid for the
Volvo car division alone in December.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile in New York, Juergen Schremp, chairman of world No.1
car-maker DaimlerChrysler, denied rumors that the U.S.-German
giant was in talks with Fiat for potential merger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
